About us

Galvanising a student
community for medicine

Welcome to Revitalised Medicine ‚Äî your gateway to insightful medical articles, resources, and initiatives. We explore content related to recent medical research and informative publications across healthcare, including oncology, biotechnology, and genetics.

üéâ

Our organisation aims to spread STEM-related knowledge about healthcare by galvanising a student community filled with passionate prospective medical providers. In 2025, we reached over 93,000 people through international media.

In the long term, we strive for revolutionary change throughout all communities, emphasising the importance of medical education accessibility and healthcare advocacy. Let's keep pushing to make an even bigger impact in 2026!

What we do
  • Publish peer-reviewed medical articles across 12+ specialties
  • Support student chapters at schools and community centres
  • Advocate for equitable healthcare access globally
  • Partner with organisations like MediQuills & CureQuest
  • Contribute EU health policy papers and position statements
  • Run webinars, diagnostics content, and a neurology library

Our Executive Team

Meet the passionate student leaders behind Revitalised Medicine.

Leadership
Enrique (Henry) De La Cruz
Founder & Director

Henry De La Cruz is an avid Southern California-based researcher on rare cellular diseases. Among some of their works include findings in protein regulation in Sanfilippo Syndrome-affected neurons and melanoma research proposal design. Outside of the lab, they enjoy promoting health advocacy as the founder of Revitalised Medicine, binging on British mystery crime novels, and indulging on daily doses of Taylor Swift.

Saanvi Talwar
Community Building Chair

Saanvi Talwar is a passionate student leader with a strong interest in medicine, psychology, and community impact. She serves as an executive for the Youth Neuropsychology Society (YNPS) chapter, designing interactive events to make neuroscience and mental health education engaging for youth. As the founder of her school's mentorship club, she empowers younger students through guidance and peer-to-peer support. üë• Balancing her Indian heritage with her Canadian upbringing, Saanvi values diversity, leadership, and compassion, and aspires to become a physician.

Our Chapters

Revitalised Medicine is expanding ‚Äî new chapters are coming soon!

Revitalised Medicine will expand out of California soon! New chapters await. Our chapter network allows student communities around the world to bring medical education, health advocacy, and STEM resources to their local schools and community centres.

Why Start a Chapter?

Chapters are the backbone of our student community. As a chapter leader, you'll organise local educational events, run outreach campaigns, and connect passionate students with the broader Revitalised Medicine network.

Home ‚Üí Chapters ‚Üí How to Start

How to Start a Chapter

Everything you need to launch a Revitalised Medicine chapter.

Starting a chapter is one of the most impactful ways to get involved. Whether at a school, university, or community centre, chapters bring medical education and health advocacy directly to local communities.

Step 1: Fill Out the Chapter Application

Complete our chapter application form. We review applications on a rolling basis and will be in touch within a few weeks.

Step 2: Recruit Your Team

Every strong chapter needs a core team. Look for students passionate about medicine, science, and health advocacy. Aim for at least 3‚Äì5 founding members.

Step 3: Get Institutional Support

Identify a faculty advisor or community sponsor at your institution who can provide logistical support.

Step 4: Plan Your First Initiative

Check out our initiative planning guide for ideas. A great first event could be a speaker talk, study group, or health awareness campaign.

Step 5: Connect with HQ

Once active, stay connected with the central Revitalised Medicine team for resources, publishing opportunities, and cross-chapter collaboration.

Ready to get started?

Apply for a Chapter

Home ‚Üí Chapters ‚Üí Organise Initiatives

Organise Chapter Initiatives

Frameworks and ideas for running impactful events at your local chapter.

üóìÔ∏è

Revitalised Medicine chapters thrive when they run regular, engaging initiatives that educate and inspire their communities. Here are some proven formats to get you started.

Educational Events

Host speaker talks, panel discussions, or mini-lectures on topics from any department area. Invite local medical professionals, researchers, or fellow students to present.

Health Awareness Campaigns

Run campaigns on underrepresented health topics, particularly those relevant to rare diseases and marginalised communities. Use social media, posters, and local outreach.

Article Writing Workshops

Train chapter members to write and submit medical articles for publication on the Revitalised Medicine website. Partner with department editors to guide the process.

Community Partnerships

Partner with local hospitals, clinics, or nonprofits to provide volunteers, run health screenings, or distribute educational materials.

Webinars & Online Events

Collaborate with other chapters or the central team to host online webinars ‚Äî great for reaching a wider audience.

CureQuest

Student-led research into cures and treatments for rare and neglected diseases.

CureQuest is a research initiative partnered with Revitalised Medicine that focuses on rare and neglected diseases ‚Äî conditions that often receive insufficient attention from mainstream research institutions. CureQuest members conduct literature reviews, develop research proposals, and advocate for increased resources directed at these conditions.

AnatomyArticles

Your Brain Has a Twin ‚Äî And It Lives in Your Gut

By Hanshika Dharma ¬∑ 8 August 2025

Light microscopy displaying interconnected nerve cells that are part of the of the Enteric Nervous System in the gut's muscle walls (Hadhazy).

You do have a second brain ‚Äì and it's in your gut! It‚Äôs called the Enteric Nervous System, and it lives in your belly. What is the Enteric Nervous System?

This nervous system controls the digestive system, and it is one of the three Autonomic Nervous Systems: the others being the sympathetic nervous system (SNS) and parasympathetic nervous system (PSNS).W hile the Enteric Nervous System works independently, it communicates with both SNS and PSNS.

The Enteric Nervous System has about 500 million neurons! That is 0.5% of the number of neurons in the brain and five times greater than the number of neurons in the Spinal Cord.

What Does It Do?

The Enteric Nervous System (ENS) plays a crucial role in our physiology, monitoring acidity, promoting bowel movement, and overseeing our defense levels. Furthermore, it helps detect irritants in the gut and sends signals to the brain's vomiting center, influencing whether the reflex is triggered or suppressed. In such cases, the ENS will induce vomiting or diarrhea while it determines and controls the movements of the gastrointestinal tract. The ENS also plays a role in controlling local blood flow dynamics in the gut by regulating gut hormone release and interacting closely with the immune cells in the digestive tract.

The Gut-Brain Relations

The Enteric Nervous System communicates with the brain through the vagus nerve and the Gut Brain Axis, the communication network between the Central Nervous System and the gastrointestinal tract, explaining various actions our stomach performs. In cases of anxiety, our stomachs are said to go ‚Äòqueasy‚Äô or nauseous, whereas during states of euphoria, we are said to get ‚Äòbutterflies.‚Äô Likewise, the mere thinking of eating food results in the stomach releasing digestive juices. Like the brain, the Enteric Nervous System uses more than thirty neurotransmitters, and 95 percent of the body's serotonin is found in the bowel. Hence, similarities between cerebral nervous systems and the Enteric Nervous System, meaning that certain depression treatments may target both the gut and brain.

Its Effect in the Future of Medicine?

Scientists are learning that the serotonin made by the Enteric Nervous System might also play a role in more surprising diseases. The Enteric Nervous System regulates bone mass to the extent that one could use this regulation to cure osteoporosis, a disease weakening bone structure. Dr.

Michael Gershon, Professor of Pathology and Cell Biology at Columbia University, discovered that the same genes responsible for forming synapses in the brain also contribute to the development of neural connections in the gut. He suggests that if these genes are disrupted in conditions like autism, it may help explain why many children on the spectrum experience gastrointestinal motor issues alongside elevated levels of serotonin produced in the gut (Hadhazy). Further work in neurogastroenterology will likely offer some new insight into the workings of the second brain.

Conclusion

The findings on the Enteric Nervous System are groundbreaking. Only time will tell the massive impact of future discoveries as well. Its strong connection with the brain means that it is significant to the neurological chemical processes in human physiology.So next time you trust your gut, know that it might actually be doing some real thinking.

References

  1. Harvard Health Publishing. The Gut-Brain Connection. Harvard Medical School, 2021, https://www.health.harvard.edu/diseases-and-conditions/the-gut-brain-connection."Enteric
  2. Nervous System (ENS)."
  3. Physio-Pedia, https://www.physio-pedia.com/EntericNervousSystem_(ENS)."Enteric Nervous System." Wikipedia, Wikimedia Foundation, 8 Aug. 2025, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enteric nervoussystem.Queensland Brain Institute. "Enteric Nervous System." Queensland Brain Institute, The University of Queensland, https://qbi.uq.edu.au/brain/brainanatomy/peripheral-nervous-system/enteric-nervous-system.
  4. Hadhazy, Adam. "Think Twice: How the Gut‚Äôs 'Second Brain' Influences Mood and Well-Being." Scientific American, 1 Feb. 2010, https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/gut-second-brain.

The Forgotten Organ: How the Interstitium Could Change Modern Medicine

By Hanshika Dharma ¬∑ 5 August 2025

Imaging of the interstitium: A) Collagen bundles within the interstitial space captured by electron magnification; B) Higher magnification of the space imaged in A); C) Microscopy identifying the fibrillar collagen within the interstitium's extracellular matrix; D) Staining showing elastic fibers within the collagen bundles (Benias et al.).

An organ: A part of an organism that is typically self-contained and has a specific vital function.

(Oxford Languages)However, a study from 2018 may change that definition for good.

"Interstitium" sounds alien to many‚Äîprobably because its nature is still being debated. But what is it in the first place? Let‚Äôs take a closer look.

What is the Interstitium?

The interstitium, the space between cells filled with fluid, has proven crucial for the functioning of tissues and in pathology. The interstitium is supported and organized by a collagen lattice, allowing it to change shape and return to its normal state with ease. It is found in organs where constant sequences of compression and distension occur, such as the lungs and the digestive tract after eating [Benias et al., 2018].

How Was It Discovered?

The occurrence of a supposed organ‚Äôs discovery after centuries of anatomical study is peculiar.

On the other hand, it has a good reason: traditional tissue sampling destroys the structure of the interstitium, draining all the fluid and collapsing open spaces.

Hence, the team of researchers used confocal laser endomicroscopy (pCLE). This provided realtime imaging of human tissues during endoscopy [Benias et al., 2018]. Fluorescein dye is injected into the patient. This lights up parts of the tissue when viewed with the laser. Under the microscope, they saw a reticular (net-like) pattern. Fluorescein had filled into spaces that looked like fluid-filled gaps. The pattern had no known match in anatomy‚Äîscientists had never seen this structure before. Normally, tissue is preserved using chemicals, but this can destroy fragile fluid spaces. So instead, they froze the tissue before fixation, which kept the structure intact. The preserved tissue showed that the strange pattern was a fluid-filled space in the submucosa (the layer under bile duct lining). This space is connected to the lymphatic system and is supported by a strong network of thick collagen fibers [Benias et al., 2018].

What Effects Does It Have on the Body?

The interstitium holds immense value when allowing molecular mechanisms to function within cells, which promotes one‚Äôs health, but it can also contribute to disease progression. One of its numerous roles is as a shock absorber. This is due to its nature of compressibility and distensibility, which results in its presence in an array of places in the human body. There is a possibility for cell signaling between the gut lumen and the submucosal space. These signals may include hormonal or immunologic signals [Benias et al., 2018]. The interstitium‚Äôs anatomical structure may also play a role in cancer metastasis, edema, fibrosis, and the mechanical functioning of many or all tissues and organs.

How This Changes Medicine

This astonishing discovery highlights significant value for researchers, and it goes to show that scientists revisiting ‚Äòknown‚Äô structures using new technologies would open the doors for more groundbreaking findings. It also encourages the use of real-time, live imaging techniques like pCLE in diagnostics. With the advance of imaging tools, a new way of looking at human anatomy is key because it may even result in cures for interstitial dysfunction in organs, which could pave the way for treatments for other conditions.

The Significance of the Interstitium in Research

Whether or not the Interstitium is considered an organ, it has certainly unlocked potential discoveries in the field of human anatomy‚Äîwith many more yet to come, including within the interstitium. Perhaps it will shine light on previously overlooked problems.This is truly the

epitome of scientific research‚Äîproof that learning never ends.References

Benias, P. C., Wells, R. G., Sackey-Aboagye, B., Klavan, H., Reidy, J., Buonocore, D., ... & CarrLocke, D. L. (2018). Structure and distribution of an unrecognized interstitium in human tissues.

Scientific Reports, 8(1), 4947. https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-23062-6

Genetic Engineering & Biotechnology News (GEN). (2018, March 28). Overlooked Organ-Like Structure in Human Body Found to Have Unique Functions.

https://www.genengnews.com/news/overlooked-organ-like-structure-in-human-body-foundto-have-unique-functions NYU Langone Health. (2018, March 27). NYU School of Medicine Pathologist Uncovers Potential New Organ, Setting Off Fiery Debate. https://nyulangone.org/news/nyu-school-medicinepathologist-uncovers-potential-new-organ-setting-fiery-debate Oxford Languages. (n.d.). Definition of organ. Retrieved August 3, 2025, from https://languages.oup.com/

The Debate of Genetic Testing

By Sumehra Esguerra ¬∑ 29 August 2025

A visual displaying different parts of a DNA strand and other important components related to genes. Reproduced from DNA, Chromosomes and Genes, National Institute on Aging and National Institutes of Health, Flickr, CC BY 2.0, https://www.flickr.com/photos/nihgov/24499222536.

Almost one month ago, headlines about mapping babies‚Äôs DNA in England hit the news. The story first appeared in The Telegraph on June 20, 2025 before quickly spreading to other media sources. It was formally announced by the National Health Service, better known as NHS, preceding the previous studies the organization had done with Genomics England, a partner organization of theirs focusing on researching genes. Although the so-called UK 100,000 Genomics Project ended recruitment back in 2018, analysis is still currently being done.

For example, in the New England Journal of Medicine, a preliminary report by Dr. Caufield from Genomics England and his team (2021) summarized the findings on the targeted undiagnosed rare diseases within 4600 participants from around 2,183 families. Their data turned out to be relatively fruitful, although it varied from family to family, and there was a general diagnostic yield increase across the range of rare diseases (Caufield et al. 2021).

A similar collection plan is expected to continue, with the government planning to map 100,000 newborn babies‚Äô DNA for the next ten years, coming with an investment estimated to be 650 million Euros (Davies 2025) but this time, under the name, Newborn Genomes Programme.

Similarly to the previous study, Genomics England says they target only rare diseases that usually appear early on in life, can be improved upon early identification and are able to be treated through the NHS. Scientists are testing for over two hundred different diseases, looking for changes in genes that are specifically linked to these diseases (Genomics England). The test includes both well and lesser-known conditions, as well as hormonal, immune system, blood and metabolic conditions that often have between one and eleven associated genes with each disease (Genomics England).

However, testing comes with increased caution in collecting DNA, which has been an ongoing debate for many years, specifically within genetic testing and use of it on a forensics scale.

Edmund Goby and R.J. Cross, two writers from the Don‚Äôt Sell my Data Campaign of the US Public Interest Research Group‚Äôs (PIRG) Education Fund, sets out the main concerns people have about genetic testing: the sale of DNA to other companies, the fear of security breaches from outside sources, influence of the results on insurance, and the little legal protection around DNA (Goby and Cross, 2024).

One real life example of this involved the company 23andMe, which was popularly used by people around the world to test for their ancestry. According to Reuters, due to some clients' accounts being hacked, genetic results got leaked, resulting in a lawsuit against the company for failing to protect almost 6.9 million people‚Äôs privacy. Further accusations were made that the company did not disclose that the hacker‚Äôs specific targets were those with Chinese and Ashkenazi Jewish ancestry before posting their information on the dark web (Stempel, 2024).

This scandal in turn greatly affected the company‚Äôs financial state, leading to it‚Äôs sale negotiations with a nonprofit for around 305 million, as reported by John Ruwitch of NPR. It had been originally announced in May that the bid was going to Regeneron Pharmaceuticals for $256 million. However, a series of following lawsuits by states resulted in the reopening of bidding, won by TTAM Research Institute, which was set up by a co-founder and previous CEO of 23andMe with the intent of using it for medical research, while still keeping original privacy policies and the option for previous users‚Äô to delete their DNA (Ruwitch, 2025).

Although parents in England can consent to have their babies‚Äô genetic information be collected, privacy remains a huge factor for people and companies alike. Genomics England mirrors this with their Study Protocol with Regulations, ethics and legal considerations being one of the longest portions of the entire summary.

No matter the overall outlook of the public on the situation as of now, it almost seems inevitable that more work will be done using genetic testing. Anna Jobloner, a sociocultural anthropologist at Harvard University, explains, the upcoming U.S. genetic counseling industry, allows for previous records of kinship to clarify possible health risks and indicate the disparities that exist within the health industry as a whole (Jobloner 2021). This suggests that there is a wealth of possibility waiting within genetic testing and analysis, but that science must also be balanced with the public‚Äôs concerns in order to be fully successful.

AI-Guided Treatment of Atrial Fibrillation in the Advanced World of Cardiology

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 5 September 2025

In ablation, a flexible tube, known as a catheter, and heating or cooling a scarred tissue in the upper chambers of the heart is being established, reflects the signals from antriventricular nodes, a part of the heart‚Äôs electrical system, that cause invariable contractions or irregular heartbeat in AFib (Cleveland Clinic and Mayo Clinic).

Amongst many of the heart complexities the patient, hospital, & physician triad has seen due to patients‚Äô unhealthy diets and genetic mutations, Atrial Fibrillation ranks among the top few ones. Atrial fibrillation (AFib), which has affected millions of people worldwide, is a commonlysustained heart rhythm disorder and also involves a sinus rhythm irregularity, or erratic heartbeats. Physiologically, it occurs when the upper chambers of the heart, or atria, where heartbeats occur irregularly or chaotically, cause palpitations, shortness of breath, stroke, and even heart failure (NIH, 2023; AHA, 2024). For many years, AFib treatment relied mainly on

medicine to control heartbeat rhythm, but the results were not always fruitful. Artificial intelligence (AI) has begun to change this situation by helping doctors treat AFib more effectively (ACC, 2024; NIH, 2023).

One of the most promising uses of AI in therapy happens during catheter ablation, a procedure in which doctors heat or cool heart tissue to destroy areas causing abnormal electrical signals that suppress uncontrolled or irregular contractions. AI incorporates a detection system that targets areas with irregular contractions by mapping them and guiding treatment (NIH, 2023; AHA, 2024). Specifically, AI-guided mapping systems, such as the CARTO 3 mapping platform, create detailed 3D models of the heart and help physicians target the abnormal areas with more precision by heating or cooling areas in the heart to create small scars. The scars block faulty heart signals and restore a typical heartbeat.

AI in catheter ablation for atrial fibrillation helps guide this procedure by analyzing real-time data from the heart. It uses sensors such as electrophysiology mapping catheters, temperature sensors, pressure sensors, and intracardiac electrograms to monitor the heart‚Äôs electrical activity and tissue characteristics. AI processes this information to identify the precise areas needing ablation, predicts the optimal energy delivery, and adjusts catheter positioning, making the procedure more accurate, faster, and safer. These benefits signify fewer repeat procedures and better long-term outcomes for patients.

The treatment of atrial fibrillation under the impactful and efficacious AI usage shows how this technology is moving into actual patient therapy. By combining advanced mapping devices with AI algorithms, doctors can treat AFib with greater accuracy and safety (NIH, 2023; ACC, 2024).

This progress not only improves the quality of life for patients but also reduces the overall burden of heart disease. As these systems continue to develop, AI is expected to become a part of everyday cardiology practice, supporting physicians and improving patient care worldwide (AHA, 2024; NIH, 2023).

AI-Powered Screening Tools: A New Frontier in Cardiology

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 19 September 2025

Project EchoNext achieved an AUROC of eighty-five percent in internal tests and between seventy-eight and eighty percent in external hospitals. AUROC (Area under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve) shows how well a test can tell apart sick and healthy patients ‚Äî a one-hundred percent true positive rate suggests perfect accuracy, while lower true positive rates indicate flaws in detecting cardiovascular conditions. These results show EchoNext is highly accurate at detecting heart problems across different patient groups.

As artificial intelligence has taken over the healthcare industry, it has proven both fruitful and innovative in some regards. The world has witnessed its prospective benefits in diagnosing and treating health conditions. Recent developments in cardiology have shown promising progress with AI-powered screening tools that can catch heart disease earlier and in more accessible settings.

A notable example is the ‚ÄúEchoNext‚Äù tool developed by Columbia University and the NewYork-

Presbyterian Hospital, which uses AI to analyze standard ECGs that are also known as electrocardiograms and can be explained as graphical representations forming peaks and waves using the signals received from heart contractions patients. Patients who may have structural heart disease (e.g., valve disease, thickened heart muscle) may be flagged, and this is helpful in indicating whether further imaging is required. When tested against thirteen cardiologists, EchoNext achieved seventy-seven percent accuracy, outperforming the doctors‚Äô sixty-four percent average, in detecting structural heart disease, thus potentially transforming routine ECGs into powerful screening tools (Columbia University Irving Medical Center, 2024). Such tools could reach patients who do not yet have apparent symptoms and reduce delays in diagnosis, especially in settings with limited access to echocardiography.

Another recent breakthrough is the development of an AI-powered stethoscope by Imperial College London and Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust (in partnership with Eko Health), capable of diagnosing heart failure, valve disease, and abnormal heart rhythms in fifteen seconds. This device records heart sounds and ECG signals before sending data for rapid AI analysis, leading to significantly higher diagnostic rates in trials, especially among patients exhibiting common symptoms like breathlessness or fatigue. A UK trial consisting of about 12,000 such patients have shown that those evaluated with the AI stethoscope were twice as likely to receive accurate diagnoses of heart failure, three times more likely for atrial fibrillation, and nearly twice as likely for valve disease compared to traditional methods (Imperial College London, 2024). These findings hint at a future where primary care settings might leverage such tools for earlier detection and referral, reducing dependence on specialist diagnostics.

Despite being propitious, utilizing AI tools has come with emerging challenges in ensuring that it can readily become a part of standardized medicine. Precision and accuracy in research settings may not always appear in clinical practice, especially in diverse populations where the data used to train AI models may be subject to errors. False positives, in particular, are a concern, meaning some patients might undergo unnecessary follow-up tests, anxiety, or even treatments. Regulatory approval, data privacy, and ensuring interpretability to ensure that physicians and patients understand how AI is diagnosing conditions are also key issues (Topol, 2019). While AI screening tools represent an exciting current event in cardiology, their full potential will depend on rigorous validation, equitable deployment, and careful integration into clinical workflows to benefit all patients.

References

  1. Bartusik-Aebisher, D., et al. (2025). Artificial Intelligence and ECG: A New Frontier in Cardiac Diagnostic Systems. Biomedicines, 13(7), 1685. https://doi.org/10.3390/biomedicines13071685.
  2. Elias, P., et al. (2025). EchoNext: AI Tool for Structural Heart Disease Detection [Study]. Nature. (Referenced via Reuters Health Rounds). Imperial College London & Eko Health. (2025, August 30). Doctors develop AI stethoscopes that can detect major heart conditions in 15 seconds. The Guardian.
  3. Society for Cardiovascular Angiography & Interventions (SCAI). (2025). New studies highlight potential of artificial intelligence to improve outcomes for patients with heart failure and cardiac arrest. SCAI Scientific Sessions.

Cardiac Amyloidosis: An Uncommon Disorder of the Heart Compared to Prevalent Cardiomyopathies

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 19 September 2025

Illustration showing the mechanism of action of tafamidis, a drug used in the treatment of cardiac amyloidosis. Cardiac amyloidosis happens when abnormal proteins accumulate in the heart muscle, causing stiffness. Two forms cause this: transthyretin amyloidosis, where transthyretin (TTR) proteins misfold and form amyloid fibrils, and light-chain amyloidosis, where antibody fragments become deposited in the heart. Tafamidis stabilizes transthyretin, preventing misfolding and fibril formation, which slows disease progression and improves heart function.

Cardiac amyloidosis is a rare but increasingly recognized heart condition caused by the buildup of amyloid fibrils ‚Äî abnormal protein deposits ‚Äî within the heart muscle. These deposits thicken and stiffen heart walls, reducing their ability to relax and fill with blood. This process leads to restrictive cardiomyopathy, a type of cardiac restrictive disease, where the heart‚Äôs

pumping function is preserved but its filling capacity is severely impaired, resulting in symptoms like shortness of breath and fatigue.

Restrictive cardiac myopathy is a heart disease where heart walls become rigid as a result of the deposits. Because of this, cardiovascular muscle activity becomes restricted. and the heart is unable to properly stretch, fill with blood, and the pump mechanism‚Äôs contraction rate deviates from standard levels. In contrast to prevalent cardiomyopathies, like dilated or hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which are frequently hereditary or based on genetic inheritance or are ischemic (lacking blood flow) in nature, cardiac amyloidosis results from light-chain (AL) amyloidosis or transthyretin (ATTR) amyloidosis protein misfolding. The term infiltrative can be used to explain the disease‚Äôs mechanism, for it reflects how cells move across an affected tissue‚Äôs barrier into a foreign location or their concentration decreases. Due to this process, patients predominantly have shown heart failure symptoms‚Äîdyspnea, edema, fatigue‚Äîyet their disease differs significantly, for it involves progressive stiffening of the myocardium and impaired relaxation (Maurer et al., 2019).

Relative to prevalent cardiomyopathies, another distinction in cardiac amyloidosis lies in diagnostic complexity. Dilated cardiomyopathy screening will exhibit a thin-walled, enlarged heart ventricle, whereas imaging in hypertrophic cardiomyopathy displays a sarcomeric muscle contractile unit mutation‚Äôs effects in significantly thickening these wall-like structures.In cardiac amyloidosis, the heart walls appear thickened, but this is caused by amyloid protein deposits infiltrating the heart muscle rather than by actual growth or enlargement of the muscle cells (true hypertrophy). This distinction is important because, unlike hypertrophy where muscle cells get bigger in response to increased workload, amyloidosis causes stiffness and impaired filling without increased muscle strength ‚Äî leading to restrictive cardiomyopathy rather than a stronger heart muscle.

Imaging techniques, such as Cardiac MRI and nuclear scintigraphy, are now critical in differentiating from dilated or hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, as they are capable of recognizing amyloid-specific infiltration patterns of infiltration, and electrocardiography cannot detect tissue characterization alone (Gillmore et al., 2016).

These therapeutic approaches emphasize how rare cardiac amyloidosis compared to other cardiomyopathies. Although beta-blockers blocking adrenaline and noradrenaline effects on the cardiovascular system and anticoagulants ‚Äúthinning‚Äù blood are effective treatments for dilated or hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, amyloidosis patients cannot tolerate these therapies due to hypertension resulting from utilizing these therapies. To avoid such side effects, disease-specific therapy, such as tafamidis (for ATTR amyloidosis), or chemotherapy regimens (in AL amyloidosis) is employed, aiming at the root cause of protein dysfunction, not merely the cardiac pathophysiology. This variation highlights accurate diagnosis‚Äôs importance since inappropriately applying standard cardiomyopathy medication can worsen amyloidosis-based patients‚Äô conditions (Maurer et al., 2018).

References

  1. Gillmore, J. D., et al. (2016). Nonbiopsy diagnosis of cardiac transthyretin amyloidosis. Circulation, 133(24), 2404‚Äì2412. https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.116.021612.
  2. Maurer, M. S., et al. (2018). Tafamidis treatment for patients with transthyretin amyloid cardiomyopathy. New England Journal of Medicine, 379(11), 1007‚Äì 1016. https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa1805689.
  3. Maurer, M. S., Elliott, P., et al. (2019). Addressing common questions encountered in the diagnosis and management of cardiac amyloidosis. Circulation: Heart Failure, 12(9), e006954. https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCHEARTFAILURE.119.006954.

Cardiac Storage Diseases: Hidden Threats to the Heart

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 6 October 2025

Fabry disease, caused by a deficiency of the enzyme alpha-galactosidase A, which is responsible for breaking down a fatty substance called Globotriaosylceramide (Gb3), is a rare inherited disorder belonging to the lysosomal storage disease group . When this enzyme is missing or is present in lower concentrations, Gb3 slowly accumulates inside cells throughout the body, especially in blood vessel walls, the heart, kidneys, and nerves. This buildup affects these organs‚Äô function and leads to many problems. In the heart, Fabry disease often causes muscle thickness, irregular rhythms, and sometimes heart failure. In the kidneys, it can result in protein loss and kidney failure, while in the nervous system, it leads to burning pain in the hands and feet, as well as an increased risk of stroke. Skin rashes known as angiokeratomas and eye tissue changes can also appear. Enzyme replacement therapy or drugs that stabilize the faulty enzyme are used to slow down Gb3 buildup and protect organs from long-term damage (Hong and Kim).

Cardiac storage diseases are a subset of metabolic and infiltrative disorders in which abnormal amounts of certain molecules such as glycogen, lipids, glycosphingolipids, or proteins accumulate within cardiac cells or the interstitium, impairing the heart‚Äôs structure and function.

These conditions are commonly characterized as heart diseases, like hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, or heart failure, making their diagnosis both challenging and critical. The American Heart Association (AHA) and American College of Cardiology (ACC) emphasize precise phenotype representation‚Äôs and etiologic (factor-based) diagnosis‚Äôs importance in their clinical guidelines because storage diseases may respond to specialized therapies or individualized treatment strategies.

One prominent class of storage diseases are lysosomal storage disorders affecting the heart and other organs: Fabry disease, Pompe disease, and Danon disease. In those disorders, lysosomal substrate degradation failures lead to cellular deposits in organs, which, in turn, cause cellular dysfunction and heart failure. Glycogen storage diseases may also lead to Cori or Forbes disease, where glycogen accumulates in cardiomyocytes and conduction systems (vessels and arteries), resulting in cardiomyopathy or arrhythmias (irregular heart rhythms). When clinicians observe unexplained left ventricular thickening or conduction defects in cardiovascular examinations, infiltrative or storage disorders may be present and are highlighted when finalizing several heart-failure guidelines and expert reviews.

Early cardiac health examinations and targeted and specialized testing are key in confirming these storage diseases‚Äô presence. A diagnostic workflow setup may include enzyme activity measurement (like that of alpha-galactosidase A in Fabry disease), advanced cardiac imaging, like echocardiography or cardiac MRI, and tissue biopsy. To confirm such disorders, diseasespecific therapies, such as enzyme replacement therapy, substrate reduction, or gene therapy, may slow or even reverse cardiac damage. Additionally, all types of supportive cardiac care, including guideline-directed heart failure therapy, direct medical therapy for heart failure management (which provides a proper treatment plan for heart disease in patients to improve cardiovascular health). Others may include arrhythmia management, where device therapy, such as pacemaker placement, which revives heart contractions in critical heart conditions, remains essential, and integrating guidance from organizations like the AHA and ACC is recommended to ensure standard cardiovascular health protocols are not compromised.

Cardiac storage disease awareness and cardiomyopathy diagnosis can lead to transformative patient outcomes, especially if recognized before irreversible damage occurs.

Artificial Intelligence in Early Detection of Heart Disease: From Diagnosis to Treatment

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 29 August 2025

In this visual representation of a clinical AI application protocol to detect arrhythmia, ventricular contraction in the heart's lower chamber is monitored using an AI-based software tool, and cardiac rhythm is displayed on the monitor's screen.

Ever since artificial intelligence (AI) was created, the medical field has had its reservations in using it. However, the plethora of advances the healthcare system has seen are by far some of the most revolutionizing at both in-patient clinical settings and at specialist staff desks at hospitals. Specifically within cardiology, AI models have demonstrated the ability to detect diseases from the widespread electrocardiogram techniques (ECGs) with accuracy not previously achieved by technology or human experts. These forms of AI have allowed medical professionals to detect heart disorders, such as valvular heart disease and other cardiomyopathies, early and improve therapeutic strategies aimed at such conditions, which

also include cardiac arrhythmias (abnormal heart rhythms) and heart failure, of which there are three major types: reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF), heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF), and heart failure with mildly reduced ejection fraction (HFmrEF) (ACC, 2024).

AI-powered advancements allow for earlier intervention and personalized treatment plans for these cardiological disorders, potentially improving patient outcomes. These innovative technological systems can aid in early detection of cardiovascular disease and related conditions based on factors like family history, lifestyle, genetics, and geography (ACC, 2023) .

AI can also analyze vast amounts of patient data to identify patterns and predict patient responses to different treatments. These worthwhile contributions made by the software based or led by AI-influence have allowed the clinician to have a personalized approach to help tailor treatment plans and optimise drugs and treatment therapies for individualized care plans for patients dealing with complexities of chronic heart conditions.

AI has indeed allowed advances in diagnosing and treating cardiovascular diseases, such as heart failure, atrial fibrillation, valvular heart disease, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, and congenital heart disease, to arise (NIH, 2024) . Patients display comorbidities associated with the heart disease that aggravate treatment plans given by doctors, which creates chaos at hospital desks. Fortunately, AI intervention has prevented risk factors from contributing to worsening conditions. In clinical settings, AI has been useful in diagnosing cardiovascular illness, improving therapeutic efficiency, stratifying and categorizing diseases, and predicting outcomes (NIH, 2024).

American College of Cardiology. https://www.acc.org/Latest-inCardiology/Articles/2023/12/01/01/42/cover-story-artificial-intelligence-an-opportunity-torevolutionize-health-care.

Recombinant Therapy for Linked Angina

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 5 February 2026

Emerging device-based and interventional strategies target refractory angina through two principal mechanisms: Neural pain modulation and myocardial perfusion enhancement processes. Neural-targeted approaches include transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation (TENS), subcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation (SENS), and spinal cord stimulation (SCS).

Perfusion-targeted therapies include enhanced external counterpulsation (EECP), transmyocardial laser revascularization (TMR), and regenerative cell-based therapies, which promote improved myocardial blood flow and angiogenesis. These approaches provide symptom relief in patients with chronic refractory angina who are not candidates for further conventional revascularization.

Linked angina is a form of chest pain in which stimuli from the esophagus triggers or exacerbates cardiac ischemia (related to reduced blood flow) symptoms in a phenomenon known as the cardio-esophageal reflex. There are a couple of angina subtypes, and one, the classical type, emerges due to fixed coronary artery obstruction. The other, linked angina,

involves neural pathways that connect the esophagus and heart, leading to reductions in coronary blood flow when the esophagus is irritated (Chauhan et al., 1996). This condition is particularly challenging to treat because standard anti-anginal therapies such as nitrates or beta-blockers may not fully alleviate symptoms, given that the underlying mechanism is partly neural rather than purely vascular (Chauhan et al, 1995). Understanding the pathophysiology of linked angina is therefore critical for developing effective targeted therapeutic approaches.

Recombinant therapy has emerged as a potential therapeutic approach for linked angina, and it promotes new blood vessel development, not to mention that it improves microvascular perfusion. By delivering genes encoding proangiogenic factors such as vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) to cardiac tissue, recombinant therapy aims to enhance collateral blood vessel formation and improve myocardial oxygen delivery. While most recombinant therapy research focuses on refractory angina (persistent chest pain from coronary artery disease that continues despite optimal medical therapy and revascularization‚Äîblood flow restoration‚Äî attempts), ideas on promoting vascular repair and endothelial function may also benefit patients with linked angina because transient ischemia results from neural-induced microvascular constriction (Attanasio et al., 2010). Recombinant therapy could thus provide a novel, biologically-targeted treatment option for patients who experience persistent symptoms.

Clinical studies on recombinant angiogenic therapies have demonstrated safety and potential efficacy in improving myocardial perfusion and reducing ischemic symptoms (Weeraman et al., 2013). VEGF-based gene therapy delivered through viral or plasmid vectors has stimulated angiogenesis and mobilized endothelial progenitor cells, which can strengthen microvascular networks in ischemic regions of the heart. Although direct evidence in linked angina is limited, these mechanisms suggest that recombinant therapy could help mitigate the ischemic effects triggered by esophageal stimuli (Dobrzycki et al., 2005).

Despite its potential, recombinant therapy for linked angina faces several challenges, especially when it comes to quelling these ischemic effects. Optimizing delivery methods and ensuring targeted myocardial uptake remain key challenges for achieving consistent therapeutic outcomes in this patient population because of their individualised needs for effective treatment. Patient responses are also variable, and immune reactions to viral vectors or therapeutic genes‚Äô expression may limit effectiveness (Attanasio et al., 2010). Furthermore, the lack of large-scale clinical trials involving linked angina therapy indicates that robust evidence for efficacy is still emerging. Future research should focus on well-designed trials to evaluate angiogenic and recombinant therapies in linked angina patients, while also integrating advanced imaging and biomarker analysis to identify those most likely to benefit. If successful, recombinant therapy may become a valuable aspect of standard care for this condition, offering targeted relief for patients.

D., & Mathur, A. (2023). Proangiogenic Growth Factor Therapy for the Treatment of Refractory Angina: A Meta-analysis. Barriers Faced by Marginalised Communities in Accessing Treatment for Rare Cardiological Diseases

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 8 December 2025

Illustration showing how implicit bias and systemic racism influence cardiovascular care outcomes. The diagram highlights system-, clinician-, and patient-level factors that contribute to disparities in access, diagnosis, and treatment of heart disease, along with knowledge gaps and proposed systemic solutions to promote equitable cardiology care.

People from marginalised communities often face challenges when trying to access remedies for rare cardiological diseases. Treatment for those conditions already requires specialized tests and expert doctors, which are not available everywhere. For low-income families, the cost of travelling to major hospitals and paying for advanced diagnostic procedures becomes a major barrier. Many patients delay treatment because they cannot afford repeated check-ups or expensive tests, and this delay can worsen rare heart conditions that need early attention (Lopez & Grant, 2023). As a result, there are healthcare inequities across social and economic

groups.

Gender differences also play a significant role in this unequal access. Women, especially in underserved regions, are often underdiagnosed because their heart symptoms may look different from men‚Äôs, causing professionals to misinterpret or dismiss early signs of cardiological diseases. Research shows that women with rare heart diseases, such as spontaneous coronary artery dissection (SCAD), frequently experience delayed diagnosis because healthcare workers are often unaware of these conditions (Harris & Owen, 2022).

Cardiological care inequities pose even more issues for women belonging to racial minorities or low-income households. Social expectations, limited decision-making power, and reduced access to preventive care further contribute to late diagnosis.

The Public Health Monitor (2025) report was conducted in early 2025 by a regional public health surveillance team in collaboration with cardiology departments and epidemiologists during a viral infection outbreak that was associated with an increased incidence of myocarditis. The report analyzed hospital admission data, diagnostic timelines, and patient demographics across multiple healthcare facilities. Its major findings highlighted that patients from underrepresented racial and low-income backgrounds experienced significant delays in receiving advanced diagnostic imaging such as cardiac MRI and echocardiography, despite presenting with comparable or more severe symptoms than other patients. The report attributed these delays to a combination of structural factors, including limited access to specialist services, implicit medical bias, and gaps in referral pathways during periods of healthcare strain. It further emphasized that gender and socioeconomic status compounded these disparities, with women and uninsured patients more likely to have symptoms initially underestimated. Overall, the report underscored how systemic inequities in cardiological care contribute to delayed diagnosis, disease progression, and poorer outcomes, calling for policy reforms, bias-awareness training, and more equitable allocation of diagnostic resources during public health emergencies.

Current events continue to highlight how income, gender, and race intersect to shape cardiological care access. Even when new treatments or clinical trials become available, marginalised groups are often underrepresented, meaning that they miss out on new research‚Äôs benefits. Community-based programs and awareness campaigns have been promising in relieving this issue, but progress remains slow. Improving access requires fair healthcare policies, improved medical staff training, and stronger support systems for vulnerable populations. Without these changes, many people will continue facing preventable barriers in receiving life-saving treatment for rare cardiological diseases (Lopez & Grant, 2023).

References

  1. Harris, M., & Owen, L. (2022). Gender differences in cardiovascular diagnosis. Journal of Women‚Äôs Cardiac Health.
  2. Lopez, R., & Grant, T. (2023). Inequality in access to cardiology services. Global Heart Review.
  3. Milam, A, Ogunniyi, M, Faloye, A. et al. Racial and Ethnic Disparities in Perioperative Health Care Among Patients Undergoing Cardiac Surgery: JACC State-of-the-Art Review. JACC. 2024 Jan, 83 (4) 530‚Äì545. Public Health Monitor. (2025). Report on diagnostic delays in rare myocarditis cases among minority populations.

Barriers to Equitable Health

By Edha Talwar ¬∑ 26 December 2025

This conceptual framework of the social determinants of health illustrates how economic stability, education, healthcare access and quality, neighborhood and built environment, and social context collectively shape population health outcomes (NIH, 2022).

Access to medical care has long been considered an important fundamental right; nevertheless, for many from marginalized groups, this right continues to be an unattained reality. Globally, these individuals continue to face disadvantages when seeking medical attention. Not only do the choices available to them drive this issue, but broader structural, societal, and economic determinants of how the practice of medicine will be conducted and who will reap the greatest benefits do, as well (WHO, 2023).

A major challenge for marginalized communities involves institutional bias within the healthcare system, which can negatively affect diagnosis, pain management, and treatment recommendations. In the United States, a CDC analysis of nearly 700,000 patients found that

Black patients were thirty-six percent less likely and Hispanic patients thirty percent less likely than White patients to receive appropriate outpatient treatment for COVID-19, even when symptoms and eligibility were similar (CDC, 2022). Additional U.S.-based studies conducted at large academic medical centers show that Black and Hispanic patients experiencing chronic pain are significantly less likely to receive adequate pain management or referrals for specialist care compared to Caucasian patients (Meghani et al., 2012). These disparities are particularly harmful for individuals from marginalized communities living with rare diseases, as research from U.S. rare disease registries indicates that diagnostic delays commonly last years‚Äîand in some cases, over a decade‚Äîreducing access to early intervention that is often essential for positive outcomes (NORD, 2022).

Disparities in socioeconomic status are also a factor that reduces medical care access and such early disease intervention. Patients who find themselves in poor socioeconomic settings are likely to access compromised healthcare coverage, be unable to pay off high deductibles, and lack transportation when seeking healthcare. Those who suffer from less-prevalent diseases face additional costs associated with genetic testing, specialist visits, and clinical trials. Patients in countries where healthcare is a government resource are also likely to face significant indirect costs and delays that serve as major deterrents (OECD, 2023).

The queer community, particularly transgender individuals, faces other deterrents to healthcare due to limited provider training and systemic discrimination, which often result in misunderstanding, discomfort, or denial of appropriate care. In the United States, a national survey found that thirty-seven percent of transgender adults delayed or avoided needed medical care due to fear of discrimination, compared to twenty-one percent of LGBTQ+ adults overall (Center for American Progress, 2024). Similarly, research published in the Annals of Family Medicine reported that transgender and gender-diverse patients were significantly more likely than cisgender patients to avoid healthcare settings because of prior negative experiences, including misgendering and disrespect (Kcomet et al., 2020). These fears contribute to broader healthcare avoidance, as evidenced by findings from The Trevor Project, which showed that many LGBTQ+ individuals avoid medical services due to anticipated stigma or discrimination (The Trevor Project, 2023). For queer individuals living with rare diseases, these barriers may be further compounded, limiting access to specialized care and delaying diagnosis or treatment when early medical intervention is often critical (NORD, 2022).

Geographic location can further intensify healthcare inequities, particularly for patients living in rural or remote areas where there is a shortage of healthcare professionals and limited access to specialized facilities. Care for rare disorders often requires multidisciplinary teams, which are typically concentrated in urban, academic medical centers. As a result, rural patients may need to travel long distances to receive appropriate diagnosis and treatment, creating financial, logistical, and time-related barriers. Telemedicine has helped reduce some of these challenges by allowing patients to consult specialists remotely through video appointments, electronic health record sharing, and virtual follow-ups, improving access to expert care without the need for frequent travel; however, limitations such as inadequate internet access and reduced availability of hands-on assessments mean that disparities still persist (Health Canada, 2024).

Barriers associated with cultural and linguistic differences also impact people from marginalized communities who seek care. Patients who may not speak the native language or have a different cultural perception of illness may find it difficult to navigate the healthcare system‚Äôs complexities in the region they live in. Miscommunication may lead to a lack of trust between the patient and healthcare providers. Trust is critical in treating rare diseases because a longterm patient-provider relationship is often required. Past maltreatment of specific communities during research-related activities has also contributed to mistrust and alienation (NIH, 2022).

In recent years, there has been growing awareness of disparities in medical care, including those spurred by such alienation and mistrust, prompting non-profit organizations to implement targeted interventions. Groups that advocate for inclusive research and improved representation in clinical trials have proposed policies aimed at closing gaps in access and equity. As a collective effort to improve the experiences of patients with rare diseases, organizations such as EURORDIS have elevated patient voices by conducting large-scale surveys, establishing patient advisory councils, and considering individuals and caregivers in policy consultations at the national and European levels. These initiatives ensure that healthcare policies are informed by lived experiences‚Äîsuch as diagnostic delays, barriers to treatment, and unmet support needs‚Äîrather than relying solely on statistical outcomes, leading to more realistic and patient-centered policy development (EURORDIS, 2024).

Engaging with policy has emerged as an effective strategy for addressing structural healthcare disparities. Advocacy and campaign groups have worked with policymakers to reform insurance coverage, expand funding for rare disease research, and improve equitable access to emerging treatments. For example, organizations such as EURORDIS and the National Organization for Rare Disorders (NORD) actively engage with government agencies to advocate for policies that reduce financial barriers to obtain orphan drugs and accelerate approval pathways for rare disease therapies (EURORDIS, 2024; NORD, 2023). Public‚Äìprivate partnerships involving institutions like the United States‚Äôs National Institutes of Health and patient advocacy groups have supported initiatives to broaden access to genetic screening programs and specialist referral networks for underrepresented populations (NIH, 2023). While these efforts have not eliminated healthcare inequities entirely, they have contributed to meaningful, incremental changes by improving representation, access, and policy responsiveness for marginalized patients living with rare diseases.

While healthcare inequities pose a complex set of problems, solutions for these issues require fundamental system-level change. As healthcare systems worldwide evolve, this reform cannot merely be an afterthought. Each person‚Äôs right to quality healthcare is a critical part of public health and social justice, regardless of their identity, financial status, and geographic location.

References

  1. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. (2022). Racial and ethnic disparities in health care. https://www.cdc.gov/public-health-gateway/php/about/social-determinants-of-health.html.
  2. EURORDIS ‚Äì Rare Diseases Europe. (2024). Rare disease inequities and policy action. https://www.eurordis.org/publication/rare-disease-inequities-and-policy-action/.
  3. Health Canada. (2024). Rural health and access to care. https://www.canada.ca/en/healthcanada/services/health-care-system/reports-publications/health-care-accessibility.html.
  4. National Institutes of Health. (2022). Diversity and inclusion in clinical research. https://www.nih.gov/health-information/nih-clinical-research-trials-you/diversity-clinicalresearch.
  5. Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development. (2023). Health at a glance 2023: OECD indicators. https://www.oecd.org/health/health-at-a-glance/.

Marginalised Communities and Access to Rare Cancer Treatment

By Moon Hoang ¬∑ 15 December 2025

A significant public health aspect harming patients with rare cancerous diseases is the disparities that they experience. Among these include financial toxicity, which leaves these individuals unable to cover the costs of their treatment, a lack of clinical trials stemming from biases against marginalised communities that could advance disease prognosis and therapy, and limited access to care that results from resource deprivation. A few strategies to combat this issue include collaborating with advocacy groups to improve access to clinical trials and treatment, spearheading governmental initiatives to implement equitable research funding, and ensure workers from all backgrounds are represented in cancer study and care to destigmatize individuals seeking employment in this field (Abuali et al., 2023).

Treating rare malignancies is a continuous challenge, where limited knowledge, prevalence, and resources hinder progress in combating these disorders. Despite efforts to introduce new

therapeutic options, a lack of access to these remains a major obstacle in underserved communities. Factors contributing to this situation include the lack of medical coverage, geographical barriers, and biases (Abuali et al., 2023).

A facet of medical coverage is health insurance, which is a major indicator of access to care and cancer outcomes in the United States. Without health insurance, patients typically have a poorer prognosis compared to the privately insured, as the former are more likely to be diagnosed at a later cancer stage (Zhao et al., 2022). In a U.S database study analyzing cancer cases in different body sites (such as prostate, colorectal, and non-Hodgkin lymphoma), insured Stage II cancer patients had better survival outcomes than uninsured Stage I cancer patients (Zhao et al., 2022). Moreover, in females aged below sixty-five, only 30.5% of uninsured patients received breast cancer screening, compared to 68.2% of privately-insured females (Zhao et al., 2022). Additionally, in adults under sixty-five, cervical screening was received in 64.9% of uninsured patients and 86.5% of privately insured patients. These significant discrepancies highlight how limited health insurance can hinder cancer detection access. Even with sufficient resources, physically accessing healthcare facilities is not always an easy task for all patients.

Accessing medical sites in person is indeed a challenge for patients residing in remote areas, for they not only have to travel long distances to receive treatment, but they also incur additional transportation costs (Abuali et al., 2023). In fact, these two factors contribute to delayed diagnosis and treatment and poorer survival outcomes for rural populations with lung, cervical and colorectal cancers (Bhatia et al., 2022). Communities living in rural areas tend to consist of more elderly populations with lower median household incomes (Bhatia et al., 2022). Within these communities, there are less demands and financial resources available for expensive healthcare services. As a result, state-of-the-art medical equipment and competent clinicians tend to concentrate in populated areas, being the urban areas. According to the ASCO Workforce Information System, out of 11,664 oncologists, only 3.1% remained in peripheral areas (Bhatia et al., 2022). The main drivers for this are market demand and the need for frequent practice (Bhatia et al., 2022). In an analysis of the Surveillance, Epidemiology, and End Results (SEER) database of 410,465 patients, patients living in rural areas had fewer treatment options and lower survival periods (46.48¬±49.70 months) compared to those in central areas (56.56¬±55.52 months) (Khan et al., 2025).

There are additional biases within healthcare that are serious issues stymieing proper cancer treatment. All patients who come from underrepresented communities, from those with disabilities to elders and individuals falling under gender minorities, experience disparities in treatment access when compared to overrepresented ones (Abuali et al., 2023). Twenty thousand elderly pancreatic cancer patients and those from marginalized groups in a 2018 analysis were shown to have less access to chemotherapy, radiation and surgery (Abuali et al., 2023). On top of that, these groups were excluded from clinical trials, thereby limiting the amount of knowledge they could grasp, tailoring to their personalized care, regarding treatments‚Äô safety profiles, and about drug combinations necessary for last-stage and rare malignancies (Abuali et al., 2023). Furthermore, racial minorities are especially at risk to certain

types of cancer, yet are underrepresented in study trials. In 207 pancreatic cancer studies by the AACR Cancer Disparities Progress Report throughout 2022, there was a disproportionate number of White (85%) patients, compared to Black (8%) and Hispanic (6%) patients (Abuali et al., 2023). However, the highest incidence and death rates of pancreatic cancer occurred mostly among Black individuals.

Acknowledging barriers that challenge equitable access to cancer treatment is as crucial as developing innovative medications for the disorder. Disparities, including healthcare coverage, distance, and bias, continue widening the gap between marginalized communities and state-ofthe-art rare cancer therapy. This situation drives limited knowledge about oncological therapeutic abilities and a shortage of specialists who can attend to these communities. Efforts to popularize insurance coverage, improve rural healthcare infrastructure, and deter bias in clinical settings must be made to mitigate this healthcare gap. Regardless of one‚Äôs background, advanced treatment and palliative care should be universal to all individuals.

References

  1. Abuali, I., Patel, S., Kiel, L., Meza, K., & Florez, N. (2023, January 9). Disparities in cancer care‚ÄîA call to action. Cancer Cell, 41(1), 1-4. ScienceDirect. 10.1016/j.ccell.2022.11.003.
  2. Bhatia, S., Landier, W., Paskett, E. D., Peters, K. B., Merrill, J. K., Philips, J., & Osarogiagbon, R. U. (2022, February 11). Rural‚ÄìUrban Disparities in Cancer Outcomes: Opportunities for Future Research. JOURNAL of the NATIONAL CANCER INSTITUTE, 114(7), 940-952. PubMed Central. 10.1093/jnci/djac030.
  3. Khan, S., Ali, A., Yetiskul, E., Bacha, Z., Qandil, H., Davis, A., Chaudhary, H., Niazi, M., Wei, C., ElSayegh, S., & Dhar, M. (2025, May 28). Racial, geographical, and socioeconomic disparities in patients with rare tumors: SEER database analysis. Journal of Clinical Oncology, 43. ASCO Publications. 10.1200/JCO.2025.43.16_suppl.e23076.

Global Policy and Advocacy Advances Improving Access to Treatment for Rare Cardiological Diseases

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 28 December 2025

Infographic summarizing UK Rare Diseases Framework priorities and nation-specific action plans, including faster diagnosis, increased awareness, coordinated care, and access to specialist treatments. This policy initiative illustrate how legislative and strategic frameworks are being implemented to improve outcomes for people living with rare diseases in the UK (Department of Health and Social Care, 2021, January 9).

Recently, governments and advocacy organizations have increasingly focused on improving access to treatment for rare cardiological diseases, which often face delayed diagnosis and limited therapeutic options (EURORDIS, 2024). One notable example is the United Kingdom‚Äôs 2025 Rare Diseases Action Plan, which updates the UK Rare Diseases Framework and prioritizes faster diagnosis, improved awareness among healthcare professionals, and stronger care coordination. The policy also emphasizes equitable access to specialist centers and innovative

therapies for patients with ultra-rare cardiac conditions, aiming to ensure that no patient is left without appropriate treatment (UK Department of Health and Social Care, 2025).

The UK initiative promotes the use of whole genome sequencing for newborns and supports pilot programs that integrate genetic testing with structured clinical care pathways, enabling earlier detection of rare cardiological disorders (UK Department of Health and Social Care, 2025). Early identification through these programs allows timely clinical interventions that can significantly improve patient outcomes and long-term prognosis (Turnbull et al., 2018). The plan also supports the development and delivery of individualized gene therapies within the NHS framework, reflecting a commitment to translating advanced genomic research into patientcentered care and reducing disparities in access to innovative treatments for rare cardiac diseases (UK Department of Health and Social Care, 2025; Collins & Varmus, 2015).

In the United States, advocacy-driven legislation such as the Cardiomyopathy HEARTS Act has established new pathways for patients to access timely care (American Heart Association, 2024, December 26). The law emphasizes increased awareness, early screening, and education for cardiomyopathy, a group of rare heart muscle diseases (American Heart Association, 2024, March 12). Advocacy organizations worked closely with policymakers to ensure patients have access to specialist centers, clinical trials, and innovative therapies, helping to reduce the impact of delayed diagnosis and gaps in care (Cardiomyopathy Foundation, n.d.).

Beyond policy, organizations such as Genetic Alliance UK and the American Heart Association‚Äôs rare disease initiatives continue to advocate for patient rights, research funding, and equitable access to treatment (Genetic Alliance UK, 2024; American Heart Association, 2024, December 26). These groups work to reduce systemic barriers by promoting inclusive healthcare policies, conducting public education campaigns, and collaborating closely with researchers and clinicians (EURORDIS-Rare Diseases Europe, 2024). Their efforts are essential for ensuring that advances in the management of rare cardiological diseases are disseminated globally and translate into measurable improvements in patient outcomes (UK Department of Health and Social Care, 2025; Collins & Varmus, 2015).

Bridging the Diagnostic Gap: Improving Access to Immunohistochemistry in Resource-Limited Regions

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 15 February 2025

Digital Pathology (DP) in modern diagnostics heavily uses advancements in laboratory techniques such as immunohistochemistry to improve patient care outcomes, but ensuring that these techniques are effective does not come without following advanced protocol.

Immunohistochemistry's efficacy in DP is suppressed through significant financial investments for Whole Slide Imaging (WSI), logistical hurdles of managing large data files, and rigorous regulatory approvals required for safety and efficacy---all of which pose significant challenges in underfunded institutions found throughout underdeveloped regions. However, enhanced cloud storage and advanced data compression may overcome these infrastructure limitations in the future. Aside from its challenges, DP's benefits involve enhanced diagnostic accuracy via AIdriven tools, reduced inter-observer variability, and remote consultations that facilitate global collaboration and prompt personalised treatment development (Fatima et al., 2024).

Access to immunohistochemistry (IHC) is critical for accurate disease diagnosis because it enables specific antigen detection in tissue samples, guiding prognostication and treatment decisions with greater precision than morphology alone (Gamde et al., 2024). In many low- and middle-income regions, however, significant infrastructural and financial barriers limit IHC service availability, meaning that patients often undergo incomplete diagnostic workups or delayed treatment consultations. Without IHC assistance, healthcare professionals struggle to differentiate disease subtypes or identify biomarkers (which influences therapeutic strategies), perpetuating disparities in healthcare outcomes compared with high-resource settings (Gbaa et al., 2025).

These disparities in healthcare outcomes are evident in West Africa, where IHC services are mostly available in major (tertiary) hospitals located in cities such as Lagos, Nigeria, Accra, Ghana, and Dakar, Senegal, but there are also Secondary facilities‚Äîdistrict and regional hospitals serving smaller towns and rural areas‚Äî lacking both the specialized equipment and trained histotechnologists required for IHC, limiting their ability to perform these tests. This shortage of trained personnel and laboratory infrastructure creates a significant barrier to implementing IHC widely, contributing to unequal access to advanced diagnostic services for patients outside major urban centers (Gbaa et al., 2025).

The high cost of reagents and specialized equipment required for IHC, which are often imported and difficult to store locally, forces laboratories to rely on small-batch materials and exacerbates existing disparities in accessing advanced diagnostic practices. In regions where manual protocols dominate, IHC remains labor-intensive and prone to variability in quality (Patel et al., 2016). In addressing these barriers, strategies such as targeted training programs and simplified, reagent-efficient methodologies have proven effective in building local capacity, enabling laboratories to perform IHC reliably. Complementing these technical solutions, workforce development initiatives have demonstrated measurable benefits in healthcare delivery. In sub-Saharan Africa, countries including Nigeria, Ghana, and Kenya have implemented collaborative programs within public and tertiary healthcare systems that provide hands-on training for laboratory technicians and establish quality IHC frameworks (Ng et al., 2025; Santiago et al., 2018). These efforts strengthen IHC preparation protocols, improve diagnostic accuracy and reliability, and demonstrate that ongoing mentorship and investment in training can overcome expertise-related barriers. Furthermore, integrating IHC services into broader public health programs‚Äîsuch as screening, infectious disease monitoring, and regional health equity initiatives‚Äîensures equitable access to diagnostics and aligns advancements in pathology with improved patient care outcomes.

In improving healthcare outcomes, regional collaborations and policy support play a critical role in effective IHC protocol implementation and standardization. Through initiatives across Ethiopia and West Africa, partnerships between local institutions and international stakeholders have facilitated manual IHC‚Äôs early adoption, enabling laboratories to follow standardized local procedures rather than relying on distant referral centers. This approach not only improves turnaround times for critical diagnostic results but also ensures that laboratory personnel are trained to apply consistent protocols, enhancing IHC testing reliability and quality

in resource-constrained settings. Moreover, integrating IHC frameworks in biomedical institutions and fostering public-private partnerships can help overcome financial constraints, strengthen reagent supply chains, and promote standardized protocol usage, thereby enhancing consistency in practices across laboratories and supporting accurate diagnostics and potential treatment decisions (Taylor et al., 2025).

Ultimately, improving access to immunohistochemistry in underdeveloped regions is not simply a technical challenge but a multifaceted effort that requires coordinated investment in infrastructure, education, and policy reform. By prioritizing equitable diagnostic capacity alongside clinical care delivery, healthcare systems can better identify disease, tailor treatment strategies, and reduce disparities in health outcomes. These measures not only improve pathology but also contribute to broader goals of health system resilience and disease control.

How Digital Markers and Wearable Technology Can Predict Neurological Decline

By Tisha Chatterjee ¬∑ 28 December 2025

Five-step workflow of digital clinical assessment in neurological disorders where digital devices capture passive behavior and active tasks during wearable or real-life monitoring (Dillenseger et al., 2021).

In the last ten years, the intersection between neuroscience and digital technologies has enabled major advances in understanding, diagnosis and management of neurological disease.

A newer innovation is the creation of digital biomarkers, objective, quantifiable physiological and behavioral data from digital devices that allow early prediction of neurological decline.

Wearable sensors and smartphone-based health trackers are other rapidly developing means toward assessing neurodegenerative diseases like Parkinson's disease, Alzheimer's disease, and multiple sclerosis (MS) in real time.

Digital biomarkers are collected in the real world using devices like EEG headbands, smartwatches, and motion trackers. Clinical visits of any kind are not needed. The data includes what people sleep, how heart rates vary, and how people move and express themselves. These subtle physiological and behavioral features reflect neurological changes. These changes occur prior to the onset of clinical symptoms (Kourtis et al., 2019).

One of the most characteristic uses of digital biomarkers is early disease detection using neurological shifts. For example, changes in motor symptoms, such as tremor amplitude, typing speed, and variation in vocal pitch range in people with Parkinson's disease may be detected several months or years before a full diagnosis is made (Arora et al., 2021). In a similar vein, wearable passive monitoring of sleep patterns, cognitive reaction times and speech coherence in Alzheimer's disease has been proposed as an indicator of early cognitive decline (Sperling et al., 2020).

Digital biomarkers also provide both patients and clinicians with active feedback about the person's neurological status and make it easier to provide individualized patient care, as patients can track their progress continuously rather than just once per year, and clinicians can use machine learning algorithms to filter through large amounts of data to find patterns and problems that cannot be seen by the human eye (Stephens-Fripp et al., 2022). This data-based approach allows for treatment and lifestyle changes before disease progression.

However, there are challenges to the adoption of digital biomarkers in neurology, including potential impact on privacy and data security due to the continuous collection of sensitive health data. Other issues include ownership of health data, risk of overdiagnosis and the need for standard validation protocols to ensure that digital biomarkers are accurate, reproducible and clinically meaningful across different groups (Coravos et al., 2019).

Ultimately, the future of neurology may involve the use of digital biomarkers as part of routine clinical practice. Large scale studies would allow for the promise of digital biomarkers across all neurological diseases. These standard digital biomarkers would enable monitoring of patients, personalized treatment and the establishment of a predictive, preventative approach. This might include a smartwatch equipped with a sensor that can detect changes in movement early and send alerts to doctors to treat symptoms before they progress.

Digital biomarkers can allow the scientific community to gain understanding into neurological disorders across a continuum, allowing individuals to take a more direct interest in their neurological health, and enabling healthcare professionals to make more informed decisions based on real world data and the latest technological advances. Patients will soon be able to live longer, healthier lives by combining predictive neurology with constant monitoring.

  2. Coravos, A., Khozin, S., & Mandl, K. D. (2019). Developing and adopting safe and effective digital biomarkers to improve patient outcomes. npj Digital Medicine, 2(1), 14. Dillenseger et al., 2021. Digital biomarkers in multiple sclerosis. Brain Sciences, 11(11), 1519.
