Recombinant DNA Technology in the Treatment of Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia

By Moon Hoang ¬∑ 3 September 2025

DNA mutations cause cancer, but with engineered DNA, scientists can now use this technology to fight against cancer. In the battle against blood cancer, particularly acute lymphoblastic leukemia, recombinant DNA technology stands out as a promising tool (Wetterstrand, 2025).

Recombinant Therapy

Recombinant DNA is genetically engineered and made by combining genetic material from different organisms. Unlike processes such as meiosis, where the exchange of genetic material between homologous chromosomes occurs, recombinants happen within a lab setting (What Are Recombinants and How Are They Used? 2025).

To make recombinant DNA, genomic DNA is first taken from the nucleus and removed from

other unwanted molecules such as RNAs, proteins and membranes. One common method for separating DNA is density gradient ultracentrifugation (DGUC), used with the mixture of ethidium bromide and caesium chloride. In DGUC, a density gradient ( a change in density) can be prepared by applying a less dense liquid over a more dense liquid in a test tube; the DNA sample is then placed on top of this gradient. Next, the tube is inserted into an ultracentrifuge machine and spun at high speed, causing the sample particles to move. The particles continue to move until their density matches the density of the surrounding gradient, at which point they will be separated (Sapkota & Aryal, 2023). Another method is to first cleanse the DNA with alkaline and salt-buffer washes. The DNA is then subjected to precipitation and cut into fragments. Restriction enzymes will then precisely cut the DNA sequence, producing a sequence with ‚Äústicky ends‚Äù, while other enzymes will digest the fragment. These fragments are then separated by size using gel electrophoresis and the desired DNA sequence is obtained.

The charge and size of particles are two factors that determine their separation in gel electrophoresis (Pandey, 2020). The process begins with loading the DNA samples into the agarose gel submerged in a buffer solution (Pandey, 2020). An electric potential is applied across two electrodes (a negative and a positive electrode) placed at opposite ends (Pandey, 2020). The electric current allows the molecules to move to the opposite pole (from the negative electrode to the positive electrode), where smaller molecules will move faster than large molecules (Pandey, 2020). Their tracks will form bands that will be stained and visualized under ultraviolet light (Pandey, 2020).

The ‚Äústicky ends‚Äù produced previously will be useful when joining the donor and the vector DNA (DNA of the recipient, acting as a carrier to transport the genetic materials into the host cell), in which they will fit like a jigsaw puzzle, forming a recombinant plasmid DNA molecule. A host bacterial cell is introduced to the recombinant DNA molecule through transformation and starts producing copies of the DNA. The retrieval of recombinant DNA requires scientists to lyse the host bacterial cell by breaking down the cell membrane to release internal cellular components (Owyoung, 2019).

In medicine, the application of recombinant DNA has facilitated therapeutic proteins and vaccine production. In the field of cancer, recombinant DNA technology has revolutionized the approach to more targeted therapies and provided more options for relapsed patients or those who do not respond to standard treatments. An instance where progress in cancer treatment has gradually emerged is in Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL), a type of blood cancer characterized by the rapid proliferation of abnormal cells that affect the bone marrow and lymphocytes (a type of white blood cell).

Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL)

ALL is a rare disease that targets children aged 2 and 5, as well as adults over the age of 50, more than other age groups. There are two subtypes of ALL: B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia and T-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia. In B-cell ALL, B cells are attacked and impaired in their ability to produce antibodies. This subtype is more prevalent, affecting 85% of childhood ALL and up to 80% in adults. T-cell ALL renders T-cells' inability to kill germs, taking up only 12%-15% of pediatric cases and 25% of adult cases (Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia

(ALL) 2025).

The cause of ALL can be narrowed down to chromosomal translocation. The Philadelphia chromosome is one common mutation where a translocation happens between chromosomes 9 and 22, forming the BCR-ABL fusion gene. From there, an abnormal protein is produced that instructs cells to divide uncontrollably. Another important translocation occurs between chromosomes 12 and 21, producing the ETV6-RUNX1 fusion gene. The resulting protein interferes with the growth of normal blood cells and promotes the proliferation of immature blood cells (The Role of Recombinant DNA in ALL leukemia 2025).

Some clinical applications of recombinant DNA technology in its treatment include recombinant Erwinia L-asparaginase, recombinant human IL-2 and blinatumomab.

Recombinant Erwinia L-Asparaginase

L-asparaginase is an enzyme that breaks down the amino acid asparagine, which leukemia cells lack and can only get from surrounding cells. A shortage of this amino acid will induce the death of leukemia cells. As there is a direct correlation between the increasing level of L-asparaginase and the reduction of asparagine, the serum asparaginase activity (SAA) is used to monitor success in this treatment. L-asparaginase cannot be found in humans; however, the enzyme can be clinically extracted from the bacteria Erwinia chrysanthemi and Escherichia coli (Juluri et al., 2022). Unlike L-asparaginase derived from E.coli, Erwinia L-asparaginase is less likely to trigger an immune reaction and is used in patients who have developed hypersensitivity to E.coli Lasparaginase (Juluri et al., 2022). Yet, the drug was in short supply due to its manufacturing scale, so a recombinant version was made, using the Pseudomonas fluorescens expression platform for production. This newer version, recombinant Erwinia L-asparaginase, was approved by the FDA in 2021 (Juluri et al., 2022).

JZP-458 is a recombinant Erwinia L-asparaginase drug and was prescribed to a group of patients who had previously experienced hypersensitivity reactions or silent activation with E.coli asparaginase. Patients received six doses of JZP-458 following a Monday/Wednesday/Friday schedule, with varying dosages in each sample. When patients took 25 mg/m2 intramuscular on Monday and Wednesday, and 50 mg/m2 on Friday, therapeutic SAA levels were achieved in more than 90% of patients within 48 to 72 hours post-treatment. These findings indicate a positive risk-benefit profile, suggesting that the therapeutic effect of this drug outweighs the risk it bears. Despite this, 72% of patients experience grade ‚â•3 toxicities, with abnormal liver function tests being the most common side effects. 25% of patients had hypersensitivity reactions, and 2% experienced severe reactions (Juluri et al., 2022).

Recombinant Human IL-2 (rhIL-2)

Interleukin-2 (IL-2) is a signalling protein or cytokine that is produced by activated T cells. It plays a major role in detecting foreign pathogens. IL-2 binds to receptors on various immune cells (T cells, B cells and Natural Killer cells), and in T cells, its binding helps stimulate the growth, survival of cell-mediated immunity. Additionally, cytokine promotes the differentiation of T cells into effector and memory T cells, thereby preparing the body to fight infections. The

making of rhIL-2 involves inserting the human gene IL-2 into either Escherichia coli or Chinese Hamster Ovary (CHO) cells - these host cells enable the large-scale production of rhIL-2 (What Is rhIL-2 and Its Medical Applications? 2025).

A study investigating an adult male patient who had high-risk relapsed B-cell ALL following a stem cell transplant involved the fact that he was predicted to have a poor prognosis with an overall life expectancy of less than 1 year. He was given low-dose rhIL-2 for four cycles, each lasting 4 to 7 weeks. The daily dosage and frequency of administration were dependent on the peripheral blood immune panels, which are blood tests that monitor and assess immune cells.

Along with rhIL-2, the patient was administered 140 mg of Dasatinib, a tyrosine kinase inhibitor drug that is used to treat Philadelphia chromosome-positive ALL as well as to slow the growth of tumors in the body (Dasatinib information for patients 2025). At the end of cycle 4, the patient NK cell‚Äôs activity rose to 9.68% compared to 0% at the beginning of the treatment. His bone marrow showed no abnormal cells, and by cycle 3, no abnormal genetic material was detected (Maharaj et al, 2019).

For adverse effects, patients receiving rhIL-2 may commonly experience fever, chills, fatigue, muscle and joint aches. In certain cases, severe side effects such as capillary leak syndrome, which can lead to organ dysfunction, fluid retention and low blood pressure (What Is rhIL-2 and Its Medical Applications? 2025).

Blinatumomab

Blinatumomab is a bispecific drug; it can bind to two antigens: one part of this molecule will bind to the CD19 antigen presented on the surface of all B cells (can be normal or malignant), except hematopoietic stem cells, which can give rise to all blood cells, and plasma cells, as they do not have this antigen, and the other will bind to the effector cells (usually the CD3 of T cells) (Mocquot et al., 2022). This binding will lead to the secretion of perforins (protein that creates pores in the membrane of target cells) and granzymes (protein that enters target cells and cuts their proteins) from T cells, thereby inducing apoptosis in B cells (Mocquot et al., 2022).

In comparison with traditional antibodies, Blinatumomab is smaller in size, allowing it to better penetrate tumours (Mocquot et al., 2022). It is made using recombinant DNA technology, where the CD19 binding region is derived from the parental murine monoclonal antibody HD37 and the CD3 binding region is derived from the parental murine monoclonal antibody L2K-07 (Mocquot et al., 2022). Murine monoclonal antibodies refer to lab-made proteins derived from mouse antibodies that target antigens on cells and spur the immune system to act against foreign agents (Myhre & Sifris, 2023). The drug is then put into hamster ovary cells for blinatumomab production (Mocquot et al., 2022).

In a clinical trial with 116 patients that investigated the efficacy of blinatumomab, it was found that the overall survival was 36.5 months (Mocquot et al., 2022). The complete Minimal Residual Disease (MRD) response, an indication that no remaining leukemia cells are in the body post-treatment, was 78% (Mocquot et al., 2022). Furthermore, 54% of patients were in remission within 18 months of blinatumomab treatment (Mocquot et al., 2022).

In another study, the effectiveness of chemotherapy and blinatumomab was evaluated in a cohort of 405 heavily pretreated ALL patients. Of these, 271 patients received blinatumomab, and 134 patients received chemotherapy. Complete remission rates with full hematologic recovery were 34% in the blinatumomab group compared to 16% in the chemotherapy group.

After 6 months, 31% of patients treated with blinatumomab remained event-free, versus 12% of those who received chemotherapy. 87% of those treated with blinatumomab experience adverse effects grade ‚â•3, and 92% of patients in the chemotherapy group (Kantarjian et al., 2017).

These pieces of evidence suggest the effectiveness of blinatumomab in clinical settings and its reduced toxicity compared to traditional treatments like chemotherapy. Yet, using blinatumomab does not come without adverse effects. Cytokine release syndrome (CRS), for example, is caused by the sudden influx of cytokines into the bloodstream when T-cells rapidly destroy cancer cells. The risk for developing CRS is largely dependent on the size of the tumor and the amount of blinatumomab prescribed. Some of the symptoms patients may experience include fever, chills, shortness of breath, hypotension and bone marrow necrosis (cells in this tissue die) (Mocquot et al., 2022). In addition, ALL patients are likely to suffer neurological complications such as severe headache, tremors, encephalopathy, aphasia and neurotoxicity (Mocquot et al., 2022). Although there remain adverse effects, the development of these therapies represents a significant breakthrough that could help turn the tide in cancer treatments.

Conclusion

The application of recombinant DNA technology has obviously broadened the treatment landscapes for ALL, offering relapsed and hypersensitive patients more targeted therapies such as recombinant Erwinia L-asparagine, recombinant human IL-2 and blinatumomab. This technology has improved overall remission rates, with some even having fewer side effects compared to standard therapy. However, patients remain at risk of suffering from fever, liver toxicity, allergic reactions, organ dysfunction, CRS and various neurological complications. Out of the three therapies this article addressed, blinatumomab carries the most significant posttreatment health risks. Apart from this, challenges such as the availability of resources and high treatment costs prevent low-resource communities from accessing these novel therapies. On that note, it is necessary for further research to minimize the adverse effects of these treatments, work on individualized monitoring and adopt welfare policies that ensure every patient has access to equitable and safe treatments.

PathologyAI Advancements

Artificial Intelligence in Neurodegenerative Disease Pathology

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 21 October 2025

AI has been incorporated in treating and diagnosing neurodegenerative diseases.

Artificial Intelligence (AI) is rapidly changing how scientists and doctors study and diagnose neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer‚Äôs, Parkinson‚Äôs, and Huntington‚Äôs disease. In the past, diagnosing these conditions heavily depended on manually examining brain tissue under a microscope to look for characteristic lesions like amyloid plaques, Lewy bodies, and tau tangles.

This process, while effective, was often slow, highly dependent on individual expertise, and could vary between pathologists. With AI developments, researchers can now analyze digital brain tissue images and neuroimaging scans much faster and with greater consistency. These algorithms are trained on massive datasets, allowing them to recognize early disease patterns that are often too subtle for the human eye to detect. As a result, AI not only enhances neurodegenerative disorder diagnostic accuracy but also enables earlier detection, which is crucial for timely intervention and patient management.

In these neurodegenerative disorders, recent AI advancements have allowed investigators to measure and interpret complex disease markers with remarkable precision. For instance, AI systems can quantify amyloid and tau protein concentrations in brain samples, predict how quickly a person‚Äôs cognitive function may decline, and even distinguish between diseases presenting similar symptoms. When integrated with advanced imaging techniques like MRI and PET scans, AI can map brain structure changes‚Äîsuch as shrinkage or atrophy‚Äîand track how these changes evolve over time. This integration provides doctors and researchers with a clearer picture of disease progression and helps in monitoring treatment responses more effectively. Through these combined approaches, AI is making neurological diagnostics more data-driven, objective, and personalized than ever before.

However, as promising as these developments are, they come with important ethical and practical considerations. Concerns related to data privacy, algorithmic bias, and the AI decisionmaking transparency continue to spark debate within the medical community. Since AI systems learn from large datasets, they are only as reliable as the data on which they are trained‚Äîany imbalance or bias in the data can affect diagnostic outcomes. To address these issues, collaborations between neuropathologists, data scientists, and engineers are becoming increasingly essential. These partnerships aim to refine AI models, improve their reliability, and ensure their integration into clinical settings in a responsible and ethical manner. Ultimately, the fusion of AI and pathology marks a major step toward personalized medicine, offering deeper insights into the mechanisms behind neurodegenerative diseases and allowing for more precise, faster diagnoses that could significantly improve patient care and quality of life.

The Role of Emerging AI Technologies in Improving Cardiological Pathology

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 8 December 2025

Various aspects of AI-based technology are coming into play, enabling advanced machinery and techniques that promote efficient and precise treatment of different forms of cardiomyopathies and other heart diseases (Golub et al., 2025).

Artificial Intelligence (AI) is becoming an important cardiological tool because it can quickly analyze large amounts of medical information that would be time-consuming to interpret. AI systems can read ECGs, echocardiograms, and cardiac MRI scans extremely accurately, helping doctors detect abnormalities such as arrhythmias, cardiomyopathies, and early signs of heart failure. These technologies reduce human error and make diagnosis faster, allowing patients to receive treatment sooner (Smith et al., 2023). Many hospitals now use AI-supported imaging tools to assist cardiologists in making clearer and more confident decisions.

Because it allows cardiologists to diagnose conditions more accurately, AI is helpful in

predicting a patient‚Äôs risk of developing serious heart conditions. By analyzing lifestyle factors, lab reports, and past medical history, AI models can estimate the likelihood of events like heart attacks or strokes. This helps doctors personalize treatment plans and guide patients before complications arise. Predictive AI tools act like an early warning system, giving healthcare workers more time to manage high-risk patients and prevent emergencies (Johnson & Lee, 2022). Such applications are especially useful in clinical setups where patient loads are high.

Another major AI benefit in cardiological pathology is its ability to support research, for it can scan thousands of studies, patient files, and genetic datasets to identify new heart diseaserelated patterns. This helps researchers understand how rare conditions develop and determine which treatments work effectively. Virtual machine-learning models can also be used to test new drugs or therapies, saving time and reducing clinical trial costs (Arora et al., 2024). The insights gained from utilizing AI allows scientists to develop more effective and targeted treatment strategies.

AI does not only enhance therapeutic advancements, but it also improves patient monitoring outside the hospital. Wearable devices such as smartwatches and portable ECG monitors use AI to detect irregular heart rhythms in real time. When abnormalities appear, the system alerts both the patient and the doctor immediately. This is especially important for patients with chronic heart conditions who need constant observation. By giving early warnings and reducing hospital visits, AI contributes to safer and more efficient cardiac care (Smith et al., 2023). As this technology continues advancing, its cardiological role will become more powerful.

AI Advancements in Identifying Pathophysiological Biomarkers

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 5 February 2025

Integration of AI-based biomarkers in various phases of data collection, processing, and resultant biomarker discovery, as shown through clinical trial frameworks (Argoty et al., 2025).

Artificial intelligence (AI) has become a transformative force in pathophysiological biomarker discovery, rendering new ways to interpret the complex biological changes that become the underlying causes of many diseases. Traditional biomarker identification often depended on single-variable analysis (examines how one independent variable affects a dependent outcome while all other factors are held constant and with limited datasets), which restricted the ability to capture the complex nature of most disorders. AI, particularly machine learning and deep learning techniques, can process vast amounts of biomedical data, including genomic sequences, proteomic profiles, and clinical records.Artificial intelligence (AI) is rapidly transforming the identification of pathophysiological biomarkers by enabling the integration

and interpretation of complex, high-dimensional biological data. Machine learning and deep learning models can uncover subtle molecular patterns across genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics, and metabolomics datasets that would be difficult to detect using conventional statistical approaches. These technologies enhance early disease detection and support the discovery of biomarkers linked to disease progression and therapeutic response (Javaid et al., 2025).

One of the most significant AI contributions in understanding disease processes is multi-omics data integration. Diseases such as cancer, cardiovascular disorders, and neurodegenerative conditions involve interconnected molecular pathways that cannot be fully understood in isolation. AI models are capable of combining diverse biological layers to generate composite biomarkers that better reflect disease mechanisms.For instance, algorithms can correlate gene expression changes with protein abundance and metabolic alterations, producing biomarker panels that improve diagnostic precision and prognostic accuracy. In oncology, AI-driven models have demonstrated strong potential in predicting immunotherapy response through the identification of combination biomarkers derived from tumor genomics, immune profiling, and imaging features (Prelaj et al., 2023).

AI is also becoming essential in discovering biomarkers from medical imaging that help predict disease outcomes and guide more targeted treatments. Deep learning‚Äìbased image analysis can pull out detailed quantitative information from radiology scans, pathology slides, and functional imaging that the human eye cannot easily detect. These imaging biomarkers can highlight structural, textural, and functional changes linked to how a disease develops or progresses. In the same way, AI-driven integration of multi-omics data is strengthening precision medicine by identifying biomarker patterns across different biological layers, reflecting underlying disease mechanisms rather than changes in a single gene (Wei, 2023).

Beyond cancer, AI-supported biomarker discovery is expanding into chronic diseases, including chronic kidney disease, where early pathophysiological changes can be detected through the combination of omics data and advanced predictive algorithms (Alobaidi, 2025). Ongoing efforts in AI development, to refine standardized validation frameworks, and improve regulatory oversight aim to ensure that AI-identified biomarkers are transparent, reproducible, and clinically meaningful. As the medical community works on these developments, AI is expected to become an indispensable tool in uncovering the biological signatures that drive disease and guide targeted interventions (Javaid et al., 2025). Collectively, these advancements illustrate how AI is shifting biomarker research from isolated measurements toward buildup of whole systems, meaningful insights that improve diagnostic accuracy and clinical decisionmaking.

Pathological Features of Liver Diseases

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 21 October 2025

Liver damage progression begins with a healthy liver and advances through fatty liver and hepatitis (inflammation) stages, leading to fibrosis (scarring), and finally resulting in cirrhosis ‚Äî a condition indicative of severely scarred and poorly functioning liver.

Liver diseases include a wide range of conditions affecting how the liver appears and functions.

Viral infections, heavy alcohol use, or inherited and metabolic disorders often cause these conditions. These factors damage liver cells and disturb their normal structure over time. The most common changes seen in diseased livers are liver cell degeneration, cell death (necrosis), inflammation, and scarring (fibrosis). In hepatitis, liver cells swell abnormally‚Äîa process known as ballooning degeneration‚Äîand some die to become Councilman bodies. The liver tissue is also filled with immune cells, such as lymphocytes and macrophages, that move in to fight the infection. In fatty liver disease, whether it results from alcohol use or metabolic disturbances, fat accumulates within the liver cells, enlarging the liver, which becomes greasy, and yellow in color.

When liver damage persists over time, ongoing inflammation and stress stimulate specific liver cells called hepatic stellate cells to become activated. These cells start producing large amounts of collagen and other scar-forming materials, leading to fibrosis. Fibrous tissue buildup creates bands connecting different parts of the liver and gradually distorts its normal shape. Over time, the liver tries to repair itself by forming new cell nodules surrounded by scar tissue in a stage called cirrhosis. Cirrhosis represents a serious, often irreversible stage where the liver becomes firm, shrunken, and unable to carry out vital functions like detoxifying the body or processing nutrients. Fortunately, in earlier stages, where simple fat accumulation (steatosis) or mild inflammation is present, the damage can often be reversed if the root cause‚Äîlike alcohol or obesity‚Äîis treated.

On an intermolecular level, the ongoing damage in liver disease is linked to several processes inside the cells. These include oxidative stress, which harms cell components; mitochondrial dysfunction, which disrupts energy production; and cytokine chemical signal release ‚Äî especially TNF-Œ± and TGF-Œ≤‚Äîthat drives inflammation and scarring.

Modern diagnostic tools have made it much easier to detect and evaluate such liver problems.

Special tissue stains like Masson‚Äôs trichrome help pathologists identify scar tissue under the microscope, while imaging tests such as elastography can measure how stiff the liver becomes due to fibrosis. Understanding how these structural and molecular changes happen in fibrosisaffected liver cells not only helps doctors diagnose diseases more accurately but also guides treatment plans aimed at preventing permanent damage and maintaining healthy liver function.

Nature Reviews Gastroenterology & Hepatology, 7(8), 425‚Äì436. Hussenbux, A. (2025, April 25). Fatty liver... how to reverse it.   2. Rinella, M. E. (2015). Nonalcoholic fatty liver disease: A systematic review. JAMA, 313(22), 2263‚Äì2273

Pathology of Renal Cell Carcinoma and Cancers Involving TFEB or TFE3 Gene Translocations

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 4 November 2025

Histopathologic image showing TFEB-rearranged carcinoma cells with an appearance characterized by larger epithelioid and smaller clustered cells around an extracellular matrix that secure them (Tretiakova, n.d.).

Renal cell carcinoma is the most common type of kidney cancer that develops when kidney filtering tube cells grow uncontrollably. Many times, it is accidentally discovered during body scans, since symptoms often appear late. When they do occur, they may include blood in urine, back or side pain, or abdominal lumps. The tumour usually starts in the outer part of the kidney. Genetic tests and understanding carcinoma cell structure assists in determining this disease‚Äôs seriousness and its best treatment (Argani, 2015).

When viewed under the microscope, the tumour‚Äôs appearance changes depending on its type.

In clear cell renal cell carcinoma, the tumour cells appear clear because they store fat and sugar, and a network of tiny blood vessels surrounds them. In papillary renal cell carcinoma, the tumour consists of finger-like projections called papillae, which are lined with tumour cells and often contain foam-like immune cells and tiny calcium deposits. In chromophobe renal cell carcinoma, the tumour consists of large, pale cells with sharp borders. Identifying the correct subtype is very important because each tumour can behave differently and may respond to different treatments (Klatte et al., 2013).

A special form of kidney cancer occurs after two specific genes known as transcription factor E3 and transcription factor EB translocate. These genes belong to the microphthalmia-associated transcription factor family. In these cancers, specific chromosomal parts switch places, forming a fusion gene promoting uncontrolled cell proliferation. Because these tumours can resemble other common kidney cancers under the microscope, molecular testing, such as gene rearrangement tests, is vital for an accurate diagnosis (Argani, 2015).

Such cancers caused by transcription factor E3 gene fusions, often called Xp11-translocation kidney cell carcinomas, occur when the X chromosome gene fuses with other partner genes, such as PRCC or ASPSCR1. This fusion produces an abnormal amount of protein driving cancer growth (Klatte et al., 2013). Under the microscope, these tumours usually show papillary or clustered growth patterns and consist of cells having clear or slightly pink cytoplasm and rounded nuclei with visible nucleoli. These tumours are more often found in minors, but they can also occur in adults, where they may behave more aggressively (Lee et al., 2022). A notable transition occurs in some cases, where genetic changes are involved, particularly those affecting the transcription factor EB (TFEB) gene. Cancers involving TFEB gene fusions, known as t(6;11) translocation kidney cell carcinomas, arise when the TFEB gene on chromosome 6 fuses with another gene called MALAT1 on chromosome 11.This causes TFEB protein overproduction, and that activates cell growth and metabolism pathways (Lee et al., 2022). Under the microscope, these tumours can show both small and large cells with pink, granular cytoplasm.

Laboratory tests often reveal specific protein markers such as cathepsin K and certain melanocyte-related markers. Although rarer than transcription factor E3 fusion cancers, transcription factor EB fusion cancers are important to recognise because they require special testing and management (Argani, 2015).

Recognising these gene-translocation kidney cancers is critical because they often do not respond to standard kidney cancer treatments that target vascular endothelial growth factors.

New therapies are being developed to block the abnormal microphthalmia-associated transcription factor and its involvement in pathways or to strengthen the body‚Äôs immune response that fights the tumour. Advanced molecular tests, such as fluorescence in-situ hybridisation, RNA sequencing, and immunohistochemistry, are key for confirming diagnosis and guiding proper treatment (Lee et al., 2022). Understanding these cancers‚Äô structures and genetic backgrounds helps doctors make more accurate diagnoses and develop personalised treatment plans that improve patient outcomes

  2. Klatte, T., Pantuck, A. J., & Belldegrun, A. S. (2013). Translocation renal cell carcinoma in adults. Urologic Oncology: Seminars and Original Investigations. https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3527899/.

Pathological Insights into the Etiology of Neurodegenerative Diseases

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 4 November 2025

This illustration shows how oxidative stress, neuroinflammation, and protein aggregation interact to cause neurodegeneration. The imbalance between reactive oxygen species and antioxidants triggers cellular damage, inflammation, and toxic protein buildup in the brain (Angeloni et al., 2022).

Neurodegenerative diseases are long-term conditions in which nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord slowly stop functioning and die. These disorders are most common in older adults, as aging makes neurons more sensitive to damage and stress. Over time, various factors such as genetics, environmental exposure, and metabolic problems cause nerve cells to deteriorate.

This gradual damage leads to the formation and spread of abnormal cerebral proteins, which are strongly linked to the start and progression of diseases like Alzheimer‚Äôs disease and Parkinson‚Äôs disease (Dugger and Dickson, 2017).

At the microscopic level, most neurodegenerative diseases‚Äô primary issue is specific proteins

misfolding and accumulating. In Alzheimer‚Äôs disease, these proteins include amyloid-beta and tau; in Parkinson‚Äôs disease, they include alpha-synuclein; and in Huntington‚Äôs disease, huntingtin. When these proteins misfold, they clump together and prevent neurons from functioning. They disturb communication between nerve cells, block nutrient transport, and eventually lead to neuron death (Singh et al., 2024).

Other harmful processes also contribute to how these diseases develop. These include problems in how cells create and use energy, ongoing inflammation in the brain, inadequate damaged protein removal, and harm caused by toxins or poor blood flow. Together, these processes weaken the brain‚Äôs ability to repair itself and increase neuronal damage susceptibility. For example, overactive immune cells in the brain (microglia) and damage from unstable oxygen molecules causes inflammation that worsens cell injury and accelerates neurodegeneration (Wider & Wszolek, 2008).

When affected individuals‚Äô brain tissues are studied, clear patterns appear. In Alzheimer‚Äôs disease, there are sticky amyloid plaques and tau protein buildup in specific brain areas. In Parkinson‚Äôs disease, circular clumps called Lewy bodies, composed of alpha-synuclein, are seen in nerve cells. These visible changes help doctors identify which disease is present and understand how it progresses through the brain. The location and pattern of these deposits explain why certain symptoms, such as memory loss or movement problems, appear as the disease advances (Dugger and Dickson, 2017).

Understanding the disease process and its causes provide a foundation for developing better treatments. Since these conditions arise from protein buildup, inflammation, and cellular stress, therapies are now aiming to prevent these processes early. Research is focusing on stymieing abnormal protein formation, improving the body‚Äôs ability to clear damaged proteins, and controlling brain inflammation. Early diagnosis and multi-targeted treatments based on these pathological insights may one day help slow or even prevent neurodegenerative diseases (Singh et al., 2024).

References

  1. Angeloni, C., Malaguti, M., Prata, C., Freschi, M., Barbalace, M. C., & Hrelia, S. (2023). Mechanisms Underlying Neurodegenerative Disorders and Potential Neuroprotective Activity of Agrifood By-Products. Antioxidants, 12(1), 94. https://doi.org/10.3390/antiox12010094.
  2. Dugger, B. N., & Dickson, D. W. (2017). Pathology of neurodegenerative diseases. Cold Spring Harbor Perspectives in Biology, 9(7), a028035. https://doi.org/10.1101/cshperspect.a028035.

  5. Parkinson disease and Alzheimer disease: Lessons from genetic studies. Neurodegenerative Diseases, 5(3‚Äì4), 122‚Äì125. https://doi.org/10.1159/000113680.

The Expanding Role of Histopathology in Melanoma: Diagnostic Advances and Emerging Techniques

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 15 February 2026

High-power magnification of a histopathological section showing malignant melanoma, illustrating the complex architectural patterns characteristic of the disease in contemporary pathological practice (Cazzato, 2023).

Histopathology remains the fundamental basis for diagnosing melanoma, as it enables pathologists to distinguish malignant melanocytic tumours from benign lesions by evaluating architectural and cytologic tissue specimen features (Wilson, 2021). Conventional histopathological analysis using haematoxylin (natural dye extracted from the logwood tree, used in microscopy and histology to stain cell nuclei to enhance tissue visibility under microscopes) and eosin staining (histological staining technique that uses eosin, an acidic pink dye, to identify the cytoplasm, connective tissue, and extracellular proteins, helping distinguish

tissue structures under a microscope) provides critical prognostic information‚Äîsuch as tumour thickness, ulceration, and mitotic rate‚Äîthat informs staging and management decisions in clinical practice (Wilson, 2021; Cazzato, 2023). Traditional interpretation for tissue analysis incorporates observations with the naked eye, which is inconsistent because it depends on personal judgment. This indicates the need for better methods that combine human expertise with additional tools for more accurate diagnoses. Hence, subjective thresholds prevent effective tissue analysis, emphasizing the need for enhanced diagnostic frameworks that integrate pathology with supplementary tools (Clarke et al., 2023).

Using enhanced diagnostic frameworks to begin tracking distinct histopathological melanomic subtypes such as lentigo maligna, acral lentiginous, and desmoplastic melanomas has improved understanding of disease behaviour and prognosis (Qasim et al., 2025). Each subtype demonstrates unique development patterns that have implications for surgical planning and risk stratification (Qasim et al., 2025). In challenging cases, ancillary methods such as immunohistochemistry, with melanocyte-specific markers like HMB-45 and MelanA, support accurate melanoma cell identification through bound antigen detection (Wies et al., 2024; Van Herck et al., 2021). Moreover, the integration of multiplexed immunohistochemistry with digital image analysis provides rich spatial and phenotypic data that enhance tumour characterisation beyond conventional histology (Van Herck et al., 2021).

Recent technological advances have expanded the role of digital pathology and artificial intelligence in these and other melanomic histopathology practices. Whole-slide imaging and deep learning models have shown promise in classifying melanoma, potentially reducing interpretation variability and improving diagnostic precision (Clarke et al., 2023; Neimy et al., 2024). These computational approaches also assist in subtype identification and tumour feature visualization, providing for consistent and reproducible analysis (Guermazi et al., 2025; Clarke et al., 2023).

By combining biomarkers within a preserved tissue context using enhanced histopathological techniques like computational approaches, professionals can gain deeper insights into melanoma tumour microenvironments and develop potential therapeutic targets, enabling tailored management strategies. Indeed, these advancements are expected to refine the tracking of melanoma progression, support precision oncology, and facilitate personalized care pathways.

Understanding the Pathophysiology of Inflammatory Diseases

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 6 October 2025

Chronic inflammation in blood vessels can lead to serious problems like atherosclerosis, plaque rupture, and vascular diseases, starting when harmful signals and immune cells (like T cells and macrophages) directly injury the vessel wall by releasing reactive oxygen species (ROS) and inflammatory chemicals (cytokines). These signals recruit more immune cells, resulting in worse inflammation. Macrophages become foam cells, which die and form a soft necrotic (dying) tissue inside the vessel. This weakens the vessel wall and causes its inner elastic layer to disintegrate. Smooth muscle cells then migrate and multiply, creating thickened layers.

Simultaneously, new blood vessels develop inside the vessel wall, increasing leakiness, causing it to become unstable. In the vessel wall‚Äôs thinnest layers, a thin cap forms over the necrotic core, which can rupture and lead to clot formation (thrombosis) (Shirai et. al).

Inflammation is generally known as one of the body‚Äôs primary defense mechanisms, designed and aimed to protect tissues from harmful agents and support healing. When the body detects injury, infection, or toxins, blood vessels in the affected area widen and become more

permeable, allowing immune cells and proteins to leave the bloodstream and enter the tissue.

These cells release chemical signals such as histamine, prostaglandins, and cytokines, creating redness, heat, swelling, and pain. The primary inflammatory phases involve weals characterized by the presence of red sharp lines on the skin and later, blood capillary dilation, causing erythema and inducing permeability that results in cells leaking from the vessels into interstitial tissue spaces. This early phase, called acute inflammation, helps remove harmful substances, clear dead cells, and prepare the area for repair.

If the inflammatory cause is quickly resolved, the inflammation subsides and normal tissue function is restored. However, if it remains or the resolution is incomplete, the inflammation can become chronic. Chronic inflammation usually develops more slowly and involves macrophages and lymphocytes, which continue to release chemicals that can damage healthy tissue. Over time, this leads to tissue remodeling, scarring, and functional changes in the affected organ. Such long-standing inflammation is linked to many characterized inflammatory diseases throughout the body, like arthritis, inflammatory bowel disease, and heart disease.

Cytokines are essential in chronic inflammation by acting as chemical messengers controlling and maintaining the immune response over time. In chronic inflammation, the body produces cytokines due to a not-properly-healed irritant, infection, or injury. Immune cells like macrophages, lymphocytes (especially T cells), and fibroblasts release these cytokines, which include interleukin-1 (IL-1), interleukin-6 (IL-6), tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-Œ±), and interferon-gamma (IFN-Œ≥). They recruit more immune cells to the site of inflammation and activate them to destroy harmful agents. However, when this process becomes prolonged, it starts damaging normal tissues, as well. Cytokines also stimulate fibroblast activity, leading to tissue repair or fibrosis (scar formation), which is commonly seen in chronic inflammatory diseases.

On a cellular level, the inflammatory response begins when special receptors on immune and tissue cells detect signals of infection or damage. These receptors then progressively activate pathways inside the cell, switching on genes responsible for producing inflammatory molecules.

These molecules act as messengers, drawing in more immune cells, increasing blood flow, and keeping the response active. While this system is very effective at protecting the body, continuous activation harms healthy tissues and creates a cycle of damage and repair.

Issues that arise due to continuous inflammatory response activation, occurring when it is not properly controlled and regulated, include conditions such as diabetes, Alzheimer‚Äôs disease, and some cancers, but many treatments aim to reduce harmful inflammation without stopping the immune system‚Äôs protective and essential functions. Some remedies include medications targeting specific inflammatory molecules, as well as lifestyle changes, like healthy eating, exercise, and stress management. These all improve overall health, as well.

In the pathophysiology of inflammatory diseases, such innate and adaptive and immune responses are reflective of a complex interplay of cellular and molecular mechanisms.

Inflammation begins as a protective reaction to harmful stimuli‚Äîsuch as pathogens, tissue

injury, or irritants‚Äîbut can become a chronic process that contributes to tissue damage and disease progression if the immune system malfunctions. Key mediators like cytokines, chemokines, and prostaglandins drive leukocyte (interleukin family) activation, endothelial permeability, and oxidative stress, leading to sustained tissue inflammation. Over time, this persistent immune activation disrupts homeostasis and promotes fibrosis (excessive scar tissue accumulation) and autoimmunity, as seen in disorders like rheumatoid arthritis, inflammatory bowel disease, and systemic lupus erythematosus. Understanding these interconnected pathways helps identify therapeutic targets aimed at modulating the immune response, reducing chronic inflammation, and restoring tissue integrity‚Äîthereby linking cellular biology, immune signaling, and clinical outcomes within the pathophysiological framework of inflammatory diseases.

Pathophysiology of Ebola Virus Disease

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 27 November 2025

Ebola viruses enter through broken skin or contact with infected fluids, affecting immune cells, which carry it to nearby lymph nodes. After the virus multiplies, it enters the bloodstream and spreads throughout the body. This widespread infection leads to damage in many organs: cell death and fat buildup occurs in the liver, the spleen and lymph nodes experience lymphocyte loss, and the kidneys develop tubular cell damage. The virus also increases the blood vessel permeability, causing fluid leakage, bleeding problems, and fibrin clots. These changes result in symptoms such as muscle inflammation, lung fluid buildup, and, in some cases, eye inflammation (‚ÄúDevelopment of Ebola Virus Vaccines,‚Äù n.d).

Ebola virus disease begins developing when the virus enters the body through mucous membranes or small breaks in the skin, usually after contact with infected blood or bodily fluids. Once inside, the virus rapidly infects monocytes, macrophages, and dendritic cells (Feldmann & Geisbert, 2011), taking control of these cells by blocking their normal antiviral signaling and forcing them to produce large amounts of virus. In macrophages, Ebola triggers

excessive inflammatory cytokine release; in dendritic cells, it prevents proper maturation and Tcell activation; and in monocytes, it disrupts normal protective functions, making them unable to contain the infection. These dysfunctional, infected cells then carry the virus throughout the body, allowing it to replicate aggressively and spread to organs such as the liver, spleen, and adrenal glands. Because viral replication is so rapid, the immune system becomes ‚Äúoverwhelmed,‚Äù meaning it cannot control viral spread, cannot activate an effective adaptive response, and enters a state of uncontrolled inflammation, which contributes to severe disease early in the infection (Messaoudi et al., 2015). A factor that increases Ebola‚Äôs severity to the human body is the way it disrupts the immune response. Viral proteins block interferon pathways, which are normally essential for antiviral defense (Basler and Amarasinghe, 2019). As a result, the virus replicates freely. At the same time, infected immune cells release large amounts of inflammatory cytokines, producing an uncontrolled inflammatory reaction known as a cytokine storm (Geisbert et al., 2003). This intense inflammation damages surrounding tissues, contributes to fever, and leads to widespread lymphocyte destruction, weakening the adaptive immune response.

As the infection progresses, blood vessels and the body‚Äôs clotting system are damaged. Harm to the endothelial lining of blood vessels makes them leaky, causing fluid to escape into surrounding tissues and low blood pressure (Feldmann and Geisbert, 2011). The body simultaneously activates clotting pathways, consuming clotting factors and leading to disseminated intravascular coagulation (Geisbert et al., 2003). This combination of fragile blood vessels and depleted clotting factors results in internal bleeding, poor organ perfusion, and tissue damage.

Ultimately, the combined effects of viral replication, immune dysregulation, and vascular injury lead to multi-organ failure. The liver becomes severely damaged, reducing its ability to produce proteins needed for clotting (Messaoudi et al., 2015). The adrenal glands may fail, reducing the body‚Äôs ability to maintain optimal blood pressures, while the kidneys often suffer from reduced blood flow and direct viral injury. These failures create a cascade of metabolic disturbances and progressive organ dysfunction that, without rapid, supportive treatment, becomes fatal (Feldmann & Geisbert, 2011).

Pathophysiology of Chikungunya Fever: A Rare Mosquito-Borne Tropical Disease

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 27 November 2025

Experimental design showing how Chikungunya virus infection is detected in Aedes albopictus mosquitoes, including collection of eggs, two gonotrophic cycles (blood-feeding and egg-laying), and adult female leg testing, as well as that of F3 progeny (offspring from three generations) due to the virus (Hon√≥rio et al., 2023).

Chikungunya fever is a tropical viral illness caused by the Chikungunya virus, which is mainly spread through Aedes mosquito bites (Powers, 2018). After entering the bloodstream, the virus first infects skin cells called fibroblasts and nearby epithelial cells. These cells serve as initial sites for viral replication, allowing the virus to multiply quickly and spread throughout the body.As the infection develops, the immune system responds by releasing signaling proteins called cytokines, which help fight the virus but also cause fever and fatigue (Thiberville et al., 2013), and this immune activity contributes to the virus targeting specific tissues, such as the

joints. A prominent symptom of chikungunya is severe joint pain. The virus targets cells within the joints, including synovial fibroblasts and macrophages. Infection of these cells triggers an inflammatory response, releasing molecules that cause swelling, stiffness, and intense pain (Schilte et al., 2013). This joint inflammation can continue even after the virus is no longer present in the bloodstream, which is why many patients experience prolonged pain. In some cases, the joint involvement resembles arthritis, with multiple joints affected and limited mobility (Morrison, 2014).

Beyond the joints, chikungunya affects muscles, lymphoid tissues, and blood vessels. Skeletal muscle cell infection as a result of this disease leads to muscle pain and weakness, and viral spread to lymph nodes and the spleen can cause temporary immune changes and fatigue (Thiberville et al., 2013). Some patients develop a rash due to small skin blood vessel inflammation. In rare cases, the virus can affect the nervous system, leading to headaches, confusion, or cerebral inflammation, particularly in infants, older adults, or immunocompromised individuals (Powers, 2018).

Chronic chikungunya symptoms are largely due to continuous inflammation rather than persistent viral infection. Even after the virus exits the body, immune joint cells can remain infected, producing inflammatory molecules that cause long-lasting pain and stiffness (Schilte et al., 2013). Recovery depends on subsiding inflammation, hydration, and, in some cases, physical therapy to restore normal joint function. The disease demonstrates how rapid viral replication, a strong immune response, and persistent inflammation shape both short-term and long-term effects of chikungunya fever (Morrison, 2014).

  1. Morrison, T. E. (2014). The reemergence of chikungunya virus. Journal of Virology, 88(20), 11644‚Äì11647. Hon√≥rio, Wiggins, K., Eastmond, B., C√¢mara, D. C. P., & Alto, B. W. (2019). Recent Pathophysiological Research Methodologies in Cardiovascular Sciences

By Ifza Zia ¬∑ 28 December 2025

Overview of patient-specific pulmonary artery digital twin development with CT-based segmentation, construction of geometrically-complex three-dimensional vascular models, and computational fluid dynamics simulations to generate pressure and flow maps (Geddes et al., 2025).

Recent advances in pathophysiological research have significantly transformed how cardiovascular diseases are studied and understood (Libby et al., 2019). Modern research no longer relies solely on isolated cellular or organ-level observations; instead, it adopts integrated, systems-based approaches (Loscalzo & Barab√°si, 2018). Techniques such as multiomics analysis, including genomics, proteomics, and metabolomics, allow researchers to study disease mechanisms at multiple biological levels simultaneously (Hasin et al., 2017). This has helped uncover complex molecular pathways involved in conditions such as heart failure,

atherosclerosis, and arrhythmias, leading to more precise disease characterization (Uhl√©n et al., 2019).

Advanced imaging-based research methods have also reshaped pathophysiological

investigations (Dey et al., 2019). High-resolution cardiac MRI, CT, and molecular imaging techniques, when combined with artificial intelligence, enable detailed visualization of myocardial tissue changes, cardiovascular remodeling, and cardiac plaque composition (Slomka et al., 2020). These tools provide dynamic insights into disease progression, including structural abnormalities and functional impairment, thereby improving the accuracy of disease modeling in cardiovascular research studies (Attia et al., 2021).

Additionally, stem cell-based and organ-on-chip methodologies have emerged as powerful experimental platforms in cardiovascular research (Zhang et al., 2018). Human-induced pluripotent stem cell-derived cardiomyocytes enable in vitro modeling of genetic and acquired cardiac diseases, providing clinically relevant human disease models (Sharma et al., 2020).

When integrated with microfluidic systems, these platforms replicate physiological conditions such as mechanical stress and blood flow, creating a controlled environment for studying disease mechanisms and drug responses (Ronaldson-Bouchard & Vunjak-Novakovic, 2018).

Together, these innovative methodologies are advancing cardiovascular pathophysiology toward more predictive, personalized, and translational research outcomes (Wrona et al., 2022).

Paediatrics

Childhood Asthma

By Sababah Subah Lamha ¬∑ 28 December 2025

Airway wall inflammation, which is not seen in a health airway, is present in the airway crosssection after an asthma attack. The reduced airflow due to inflamed airway walls will usually result in wheezing, coughing, and chest tightness (Hebron Pediatrics, 2018).

Asthma is a long term respiratory illness with diagnosis of this common chronic illness present in around fourteen percent of children worldwide and is commonly known for its large prepubescent male demographic. Furthermore, the condition ranks amongst the top twenty for the global ranking in disability adjusted life years, with mortality rates in children globally ranging from 0.0 to 0.7 per 100,000. Its severity is gauged with symptom duration, medication use, and lung health status (Asher et al., 2014; Martin et al., 2022; Trivedi et al., 2019).

This disorder is associated with a hyperresponsive bronchial function that results in bronchial wall inflammation, which influences reduced lung function and its severity. This is a response to particular triggers: allergens, respiratory infections, and medication. Genetics also play a role in

asthma arising. Many segregation studies (statistical methods analyzing family data to determine how traits or diseases are inherited) suggest that a major gene could be involved in asthma. Twin studies have also shown evidence for genetic influences in asthma. Linkage, association studies and genome-wide screening suggest that multiple genes are involved in the pathogenesis of asthma. At least four regions of the human genome, chromosomes 5q31-33, 6p21.3, 11q13 and 12q14.3-24.1, contain genes associated with asthma and associated phenotypes. Genes that are involved in asthma development and outcomes will continue being discovered. This will provide greater insight into identifying individuals at risk of asthma, spearheading early prevention initiatives, and fostering greater understanding for guiding therapeutic intervention in asthma (Los et al., 1999).

Symptoms that arise due to these causes for asthma include wheezing, dyspnea, and chest tightness. These symptoms induce unpleasant sensations in patients and are a burden for caregivers to address (Martin et al., 2022). Many asthma patients have experienced frequent sleep disturbances (up to 34% percent of patients had reported this), many school absences (23‚Äì51%), and significant activity limitation (47%) (Carlsen & Pijnenberg, 2015). Caregivers also report missed work days and financial challenges as a result, as well (Martin et al., 2022).

Although caregivers report financial hardship due to child asthma intervention, evidence of socioeconomic burden, including those related to direct costs, such as medication and healthcare utilisation, as well as indirect costs, like absenteeism from work and school and productivity loss, is lacking in most countries. However, it has been suggested that improved national focus on diagnosis, disease control, and education within healthcare may simultaneously reduce asthma‚Äôs costs and management (Carlsen & Pijnenberg, 2015).

The Finnish National Asthma Programme, which was launched in 1994, considered asthma management as a community problem, where primary healthcare‚Äôs role was emphasized.

Optimal asthma intervention involves clear communication between health care professionals.

Referral letters are an accepted tool for evaluation of the communication process. The aim of this study was to assess the quality of asthma-related referral letters. Twenty-one percent of the referral letters were graded ‚Äúgood,‚Äù thirty-four percent ‚Äúsatisfactory,‚Äù and forty-five percent ‚Äúpoor.‚Äù Information on wheezing, smoking habits and current medication was mentioned in forty-four percent, forty-two percent, and forty-one percent of each graded category for the asthma letters, respectively. The Finnish National Asthma Programme thus calls for optimizing communication between doctors. The proportion of ‚Äúpoor‚Äù-graded letters was fifty percent higher than the preset standard and clearly indicates a need for communication improvements. The study found several issues in those letters that need to be communicated better, such as smoking, lung function tests, and medication, when referring to a patient with suspected asthma (Tuomisto et al., 2007).

A critical facet of communication about asthma involves identifying triggers, which supports environmental prevention. These triggers may be allergenic or nonallergenic: Allergenic triggers include indoor allergens, such as house dust mites (HDMs), outdoor allergens, such as pollens and molds, and pets. Cockroach allergens contribute to asthma morbidity, not to mention

mouse allergens that are mostly found in inner-city dwellings, albeit their implication in asthma morbidity is debated. In the outdoors, pollen can induce seasonal asthma in sensitized individuals (Gautier & Charpin, 2017).

Nonallergenic triggers include viral infections, active and passive smoking, and occupational exposures. Viral infection is the main asthma trigger in children. Active smoking is associated with higher asthma morbidity, and smoking cessation interventions should be personalized.

Passive smoking is also a risk factor for asthma exacerbation. Furthermore, air pollution levels have been linked with asthmatic symptoms, a decrease in lung function, and increased emergency room visits and hospitalizations. Air pollutants also affect indoor air quality, and they can be found in cigarette smoke and include volatile organic compounds found in building and cleaning materials. Occupational exposures include work-exacerbated and work-related asthma (Gautier & Charpin, 2017).

Avoiding these allergens and risk factors is difficult, but although individuals face challenges, there are strategies that have been implemented to improve avoidance. For pollen, avoidance relies on preventing it from entering residencies and on minimizing seasonal outdoor exposure.

For smoking, public bans have led to less hospitalizations of asthmatic children. Since avoidance is not easy to achieve, clean air policies remain the most effective strategy. (Gautier & Charpin, 2017).

Childhood asthma exists as a common chronic disease with hyperresponsive bronchial function, significantly impairing affected children‚Äôs quality of life. It hinders both physical and mental growth if physical activity and sleep are limited and results in regular absence from school and social affairs, placing a burden for both patients and caretakers. This, in turn, creates financial issues when paired with ongoing medication and treatment costs. However, evidence-based research has shown that if asthma is treated as a community problem alongside effective management through early diagnosis, suitable healthcare communication, and public health measures, the medical community can significantly decrease severity and socioeconomic impact. Asthma‚Äôs global impact could be greatly reduced through continued research and essential coordinated care.

Paediatrics

Food Protein-Induced Enterocolitis Syndrome

By Sababah Subah Lamha ¬∑ 8 January 2026

Any food allergen may act as a trigger for FPIES. However, there are certain foods that are more likely to cause a reaction than others, such as soy products and milk. Some other common triggers include grains, turkey and chicken, and squash. It is entirely plausible for the patient to have multiple triggers, though only having one or two is more common (Blamires, n.d.).

Food protein-induced enterocolitis syndrome (FPIES) is a non‚ÄìIgE-mediated food allergy characterised by a gastrointestinal food hypersensitivity disorder that manifests with projectile, repetitive emesis (vomiting) that can be followed by diarrhoea and be accompanied by lethargy, hypotonia, and metabolic derangements depending on the severity of the patient‚Äôs condition (Nowak-Wƒôgrzyn et al., 2020). Decreased body temperature and thrombocytosis (high blood platelet count) emerge as additional features of the syndrome. FPIES usually starts in infancy and typically resolves by ages 3-5, although onset at older ages is being increasingly reported and recognised (Nowak-Wƒôgrzyn et al., 2017).

Although FPIES‚Äôs pathophysiology has not yet been well established, current evidence suggests that food protein-activated intestinal lymphocytes release inflammatory cytokines, which, in turn, increase intestinal permeability, cause malabsorption, and lead to diarrhoea, among other symptoms. Decreased intestinal transforming growth factor-beta (TGF-Œ≤) concentration and increased tumour necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-Œ±) concentration may be important in FPIES. Cow's milk and soy are FPIES‚Äôs most common causes, but cereal grains (rice, oat, and barley), fish, poultry, and vegetables may also cause FPIES (Nowak-Wƒôgrzyn et al., 2009).

Indeed, many dietary triggers lead to this syndrome‚Äôs development, with both severe and mild reactions occurring with the food involved. Particularly, rice is the most common solid food causing FPIES. Rice FPIES is associated with more severe reactions than other foods. Infants presenting acute symptoms may be hypothermic (<36¬∞C) and have thrombocytosis. Indicators of hypoalbuminemia, a condition with low levels of albumin protein in the blood leading to fluid buildup (oedema) and impaired substance transport, and a weight gain of less than 10 g/day, helps to differentiate chronic infantile cow's milk FPIES from infectious causes. In this condition, gastric juice leukocytes of more than ten cells per High-Power Field (HPF), or area visible under the highest magnification, are found in infants with oral insensitivities to cow's milk (NowakWƒôgrzyn et al., 2009).

Unfortunately, misdiagnosis, such as the inability to differentiate between cow‚Äôs milk FPIES and infectious disease FPIES, and diagnostic delays for children with this condition are common.

Diagnosis can be challenging due to a broad list of potential diseases or conditions that could explain the patient's symptoms (Sohini et al., 2023). A lack of effective disease biomarker identification is also an issue that leads to diagnostic challenges. FPIES is a clinical diagnosis, with allergy testing playing a very limited role, if any. Medically-supervised oral food challenges are used to monitor the disease, which generally occurs in early childhood (Sheeba and Varshney, 2018). This leads many children to undergo unnecessary, often painful investigations.

Children frequently experience multiple episodes before correct diagnoses are made (NowakWƒôgrzyn et al., 2017).

Over the past two decades, significant progress has been made to further the scientific community‚Äôs understanding of FPIES epidemiology and clinical phenotype characterisation. The first international consensus guidelines were published in 2017 to improve FPIES diagnosis and management. However, FPIES remains an enigma with incompletely understood pathophysiology, limited strategies to identify diagnostic biomarkers, and no therapeutic strategies to accelerate resolution. These unmet needs warrant future investigations to improve FPIES patient care (Nowak-Wƒôgrzyn et al., 2017).

Paediatrics

Artificial Intelligence: Revolutionising Today's Paediatric Allergy Care

By Sababah Subah Lamha ¬∑ 17 January 2026

Allergies detrimentally affect children not only physically, but also mentally. Most significantly, sleep deprivation may cause severe adverse reactions that are heavily interconnected with academic decline and absence from school. The latter, linked with chronic sickness, can cause a lack of social interaction, leading to behavioral issues and mental illness development (Hamelmann et al, 2024).

Whether one looks at it historically or through today‚Äôs lens, the prevalence of paediatric allergies cannot be denied with conditions like asthma, allergic rhinitis (AR), and atopic dermatitis (AD), which have affected hundreds of millions of people worldwide, ever-present (Cilluffo et al., 2025). A question arises with this in consideration: How should the care provided evolve in response to these allergies?

These conditions are widespread and severe, where in 2019, it was estimated that approximately 81 million children suffered from asthma, and 5.6 million children were diagnosed with AD globally. Furthermore, data from the World Allergy Organization (WAO) indicate that up to forty percent of the global population exhibits sensitisation to environmental allergens, as evidenced by allergen-specific immunoglobulin E (IgE) antibody presence. This illness deteriorates patients‚Äô quality of life, causes financial instability, and, most notably, induces emotional and physical harm. One of this condition‚Äôs physical symptoms‚Äî which does lead to emotional distress to those close to the patient and takes a financial toll when medical attention is sought for it‚Äîinvolves life-threatening anaphylaxis reactions in which the immune system releases chemicals, causing airways to narrow and blood pressure to drop rapidly, leading to shock (Cilluffo et al., 2025).

Unfortunately, given the allergenic disorders and their underlying mechanisms‚Äô heterogeneities, conventional diagnostic and therapeutic approaches may fail to provide precise, personalised care. (Cilluffo et al., 2025). This is where AI comes into the conversation, and it is used in symptom monitoring. Allergy forecasting, which predicts allergen levels like pollen and mold spores, has become increasingly important in managing allergenic diseases.

For example, environmental monitoring systems track weather patterns, airborne particles, and pollutants, and AI has been used in enhancing this technique to detect conditions that trigger allergic reactions. AI has been pivotal in addressing the issue of climate change making it more challenging to maintain accurate pollen calendars. Shifting weather patterns and regional variations in climate effects have led to inconsistencies, complicating predictions of allergen exposure. AI advancements have improved forecasting models‚Äô accuracies, allowing clinicians and patients to receive real-time alerts. These models integrate environmental monitoring with predictive analytics, accounting for broader environmental and climate factors (Null et al., 2025).

Another quandary relative to allergenic disorders that AI has helped to address are the challenges in prescribing allergen immunotherapy. particularly in regions like Southern Europe, where polysensitization rates and cross-reactivity among multiple pollen coexist during the same season. To address these difficulties, the @lT2020 algorithm was developed, which is a clinical decision support system for SAR based on a three-step process: gathering clinical history and sensitisation data, refining allergens through Component-Resolved Diagnostics (CRD), which identifies specific proteins within allergens to identify what causes allergic reactions, and using an electronic diary (eDiary) to match symptoms with pollination periods. This structured methodology significantly enhances allergen identification precision, leading to more effective allergen immunotherapy prescriptions using allergy specialists‚Äô and general practitioners‚Äô diagnostics based on retrospective clinical history and sensitisation to whole extracts (Null et al., 2025).

Furthermore, Al may facilitate personalised treatment development by predicting patient responses based on genetic profiles, medical histories, and environmental factors. Machine Learning (ML) models can assess medications‚Äô or immunotherapy protocols‚Äô efficacies for each patient, optimising treatment plans to maximise benefits and minimize side effects (Fazlali et

al., 2025). Notably, Al is pivotal in addressing immunotherapeutic complexities, a cornerstone in allergy treatment (Null et al., 2025).

While AI‚Äôs potential in allergy care is immense, its implementation presents several pressing challenges. Foremost among these is data privacy. AI systems rely on extensive sensitive patient data, prompting significant concerns about confidentiality and security. Adherence to regulatory frameworks, such as the General Data Protection Regulation, is imperative to safeguard patient information. Furthermore, AI models are prone to algorithmic bias‚Äôs influence. When the training dataset does not represent heterogeneous populations, AI systems may yield biased outcomes when used in real-world settings, potentially resulting in inequitable healthcare deliveries (Null et al., 2025).

Al must complement, rather than disrupt, the patient-provider relationship, and maintain a patient-centred approach to avoid issues with regards to those seeking allergy care. To achieve this, clinicians need comprehensive education and training in AI applications, which should begin at the university level and continue through professional development programs.

Establishing robust infrastructure and technological tools, particularly in public health systems, is also essential to ensuring AI-driven solutions‚Äô integrity. AI should complement, not replace, human judgment. Clinicians must maintain a patient-centred approach, using AI to enhance their expertise rather than overshadow it (Null et al., 2025).

AI-driven algorithms, particularly machine learning and deep learning, have enabled the identification of complex molecular patterns and predictive markers in allergies, such as IgE levels. AI integration techniques have uncovered unique immune response signatures, providing insights into molecular mechanisms driving allergic reactions. These innovations have advanced diagnostic accuracy, treatment personalisation, and real-time monitoring capabilities, especially in allergen immunotherapy. With correct procedures considering all and any setbacks, healthcare professionals can safely and effectively use AI to our advantage without fail.

References

  1. Cilluffo, G., Bajowala, S., Elliott, T., Gupta, P., Volertas, S., & Ferrante, G. (2025). The future of allergy management: How artificial intelligence is changing the game. AI-Driven Biomarker Discovery and Personalized Allergy Treatment: Utilizing Machine Learning and NGS. Current allergy and asthma reports, 25(1), 27. https://doi.org/10.1007/s11882-025-01207-8.

Paediatrics

Duchenne Muscular Dystrophy

By Sababah Subah Lamha ¬∑ 17 January 2026

Experimental medication and therapy are available for patients diagnosed with Duchenne Muscular Dystrophy. In targeting symptoms, usage guidelines have been improved for exonskipping drugs (e.g., Eteplirsen, Amondys 45, Vyondys 53, Viltepso) and gene therapies (e.g., Elevidys) for eligible patients. Monitoring methods, such as lung volume recruitment (cough assist) and non-invasive ventilation (e.g., BiPAP), are critical in managing muscle weaknesses arising as a result of the disorder. Besides medication and monitoring, physical therapy is crucial in preventing contractures and preserving muscle function (Shapiro, 2025).

Duchenne Muscular Dystrophy (DMD) is an X chromosome-linked disorder which is a severe, progressive, muscle-wasting disease that leads to movement difficulties and, eventually, the need for assisted ventilation. Mutations in DMD (encoding dystrophin, a muscle and nerve protein that links the extracellular matrix to nerves) that abolish dystrophin production in muscle causes this disease. Muscles without dystrophin are more sensitive to damage, resulting in progressive muscle tissue and function loss, in addition to cardiomyopathy, a disease that

causes the heart muscle to become enlarged, thick, or rigid, which reduces the heart's ability to pump blood effectively (Duan et al., 2021).

Degenerative muscular symptoms are associated with DMD, which has an incidence of one in five thousand males and presents in early childhood with proximal muscle weakness. Untreated patients become wheelchair-bound by twelve-years-of-age and typically die of cardiorespiratory complications in their late teens or early twenties, with the mean age of diagnosis being five years (Yiu et al., 2015).

In light of this symptomatic progression, an opt-in screening programme that aimed to reduce diagnostic delays, permit reproductive choice in women who were expecting children with this disorder, and allow for proper childcare planning was introduced in Wales in 1990. Newborn blood samples were collected routinely as part of this programme. During the twenty-year period, 369,780 bloodspot cards were received from male infants, which, through research, had produced 13 false-negative cases. DMD incidence in Wales was 1:5136 during this period, which is lower than the 1:4046 ratio that was seen before screening commenced because the screening had reduced diagnostic delay, enabling reproductive choice for affected patients‚Äô parents and earlier therapeutic administration (Moat et al., 2013).

Some studies that have been pivotal in expanding the scientific community‚Äôs understanding of DMD progression and reducing diagnostic delay involve one exploring Forced Vital Capacity (FVC) and Sniff Nasal Inspiratory Pressure (SNIP), which have been confirmed to be among the most important parameters in monitoring DMD. FVC and SNIP are essential for identifying the shift to a decline in respiratory function that occurs in the early teenage years. An FVC value lower than 2.1 L indicates reduced cough peak flow, and an FVC below 1 L is a strong predictor of severe oxygen desaturation, mortality risk, and the need for immediate, intensive respiratory support. Expiratory muscle strength, assessed by a Pgas cough test (that contains specialized, objective measurements used to assess abdominal muscle and cough strength) and the diaphragmatic tension-time index, which was used as an endurance index, was reported for the first time in a cohort study of twenty-eight boys with DMD to monitor respiratory muscle weakness. The study concluded that these measures provided a better understanding of the respiratory pathophysiology in neuromuscular disease, particularly in DMD‚Äôs later stages (Khirani et al., 2014).

Multidisciplinary care guidelines for Duchenne muscular dystrophy that address genetic diagnosis and disease management throughout its stages have been established. Additionally, many therapies have focused on managing symptoms and slowing progression through corticosteroids and physical therapy, alongside newer treatments like Givinostat medication that targets inflammation, restores the missing dystrophin protein, and modifies disease progression. Several of these therapies have received regulatory approval (notably by the FDA), while many others are in late-stage clinical development. (Duan et al., 2021).

Other guidelines involving disease diagnosis and management, such as CPGs (clinical practice guidelines), have emerged, and they could be useful in improving care while simultaneously

reducing harmful or ineffective patient interventions. Clinical Practice Guidelines (CPGs) are vital tools for Registered Dietitians (RDs) and Registered Dietitian Nutritionists (RDNs) and are designed to translate complex, evidence-based research into actionable, transparent, and standardized care. For these reasons, guidelines for RD practices must provide recommendations with the best available evidence (Malaga et al., 2024).

In support of effective recommendations for patient care that involve the best evidence, a 2024 study aimed to identify effective CPGs for DMD diagnosis and management through methodology evaluations and clinical practice recommendation comparisons. Three CPGs published or updated between 2015 and 2020 were selected, and it was concluded that all the guidelines displayed adequate methodological rigor but presented pitfalls in stakeholder involvement and applicability domains. Recommendations were consistent across CPGs on steroid treatment, except for minor differences in dosing regimens. However, the recommendations were different for new drugs, which can be attributed to variations in evidence (Malaga et al., 2024). Differences in guideline update timeliness, and the lack of direct head-to-head comparisons against established, cost-effective treatments result in pharmaceutical innovations occurring faster than guidelines can be updated. Utilization of a drug may be the subject of specific guidelines shortly after regulatory approval, but other guidelines may be omitted or ignored because of update infrequencies.

Current and reliable CPGs are critical in effective DMD diagnosis and management. Although there have been challenges in developing CPG recommendations for RDs, progressive studies and research has improved these guidelines, especially in DMD therapy. Recent DMD guideline reviews indicate that, despite shortcomings in stakeholder involvement, the methodological rigor of the guidelines has improved significantly over the last decade. Through efforts such as those by the TREAT-NMD network and the CDC, a robust consensus that these rigorous guidelines can improve treatment quality has emerged.

Pediatric pulmonology 49.5 (2014): 473-481. Malaga, Marco, et al. "Clinical practice guidelines for the diagnosis and management of Duchenne muscular dystrophy: a scoping review."
