Paediatrics

Treating Neuromuscular Disorders in Children

By Sababah Subah Lamha ¬∑ 11 February 2026

Neuromuscular disorder (NMD) classifications are performed systematically through structural changes, using tools such as classifiers to analyse variants in genes that cause this condition.

This classification identifies the specific type of coding variant associated with splicing alterations that causes the NMD-targeted transcript (Marchant et al., 2024).

Neuromuscular disorders encompass diseases associated with the peripheral nervous system, which includes the peripheral nerve, the neuromuscular junction, and the muscle. Generally, abnormal muscle function is an aspect of neuromuscular disorders and can include chronic signs and symptoms related to muscle weakness, such as joint contractures, skeletal deformities (particularly scoliosis), and respiratory failure. It also includes dynamic impairments: such as exercise intolerance, pain in muscles, known as myalgia, and fatigable weakness, which may exist with normal intervening muscle function‚Äîsuch as coordinated skeletal muscle operation of skeletal muscles to produce voluntary movements, that indicate stabilized joints, or to maintain posture. (Dowling et al., 2018). Generally, these symptoms are

lifelong morbidities, which are often severely disabling, and at the most extreme cases, these disorders can lead to complete paralysis and premature death. (Dowling et al., 2018) Current clinical management of SMA (Spinal Muscular Atrophies) relies upon proactive measures to combat progressive motor weaknesses leading to paralysis, including aggressive respiratory infection treatment, ventilatory support, and interventions for skeletal deformities.

However, without care guidelines to improve patient outcomes and ensure treatments are based on the latest, high-quality evidence, clinicians found many decisions overwhelming when contemplating which treatment would be best for which specific patient condition in regards to underlying causes involving family history or environment exposure (Dowling et al., 2018).

Therefore, consensus care guidelines were completed in 2007 and were recently updated at a European Neuromuscular Centre (ENMC) meeting in February 2016 in light of providing care guidelines and support for patients. New therapeutic products under development for SMA can be divided into two major categories: Genetic based therapies, such as SMN1 gene replacement therapy or SMN2 upregulation or modification, and non-genetic type therapies, such as neuroprotective strategies. For example, the development and clinical implementation of Spinraza, the first disease modifying therapy approved for SMA, is shaping treatment considerations and care standards (Dowling, James J., et al. (2018)).

Spinraza targets SMA‚Äôs unique genetics (SMN1 mutations in all patients, with SMN2 copy number as the primary disease modifier), which provides a clear precedent for therapeutic development, namely increasing protein production from the intact SMN2. Specific strategies leading to increased protein production include manipulating the SMN2‚Äôs promoter region to increase the number of its copies and alternating its splicing to include exon 7, generating a fully functional SMN gene transcript. This methodological development built on historical attempts to upregulate SMN2 through histone deacetylase inhibitors that increase transcription from the SMN2 locus. While these trials were unsuccessful, they provided a critical roadmap for the current clinical trials to develop treatment for this disease.

One therapy that was developed in these trials was Nusinersen, an antisense oligonucleotide (AON) originally developed by Ionis Pharmaceuticals, that targets SMN2 exon 7‚Äôs splice site, resulting in exon 7‚Äôs inclusion in the final transcript. Due to poor transport across the blood brain barrier, it must be given via intrathecal injection. The product has shown much promise in preclinical and early phase human trials (Chiriboga et al., 2016). In an ongoing open label extension study in infants with SMA Type 1, where patients, treated with Nusinersen, and researchers were aware of the drugs being administered, subjects‚Äô muscle function scores, a clinical tool used to evaluate a patient's muscle strength and resistance, increased‚Äîmost notably improvement in motor function, upper limb function. Electrophysiology markers, especially when motor neurons are concerned, and lifespan-related outcomes showed favorable improvement, as well (Dowling et al., 2018).

Given that SMA Type 1 results from SMN1‚Äôs loss-of-function mutation, the SMN1 gene deletion or mutation results in critically low levels of SMN protein, which is essential for assembling

splicing machinery (snRNPs) and supporting motor neuron survival. Motor neurons are vulnerable to this deficiency, and this causes severe muscle atrophy, but gene therapy to replace dysfunctional SMN1 and target this disorder is a strategy that can target this disorder.

Gene therapy with AAV9 virus and full length SMN1 that accomplishes this has been attempted via intrathecal delivery in a phase 1 clinical trial in infants with SMA Type I at the Nationwide Children's Hospital in Ohio. Encouraging results and a favorable safety profile have been presented at recent academic forums; all 15 study participants are still surviving and do not require 16 hours or more of ventilation per day (Mendell et al., 2017).

A frequent symptom of SMA1 is leg pain and cramps, and massages, ibuprofen doses, or transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation (TENS) serve as temporary relief. A significant number of children exhibited non-organic or psychosomatic pain, physical pain triggered or exacerbated by mental stress, emotional, or psychological factors. It manifests as physical symptoms, such as headaches, back pain, or digestive issues, that are often linked to trauma, depression, or anxiety (Strehle, 2009).

These treatments‚Äîthough precise, as they have targeted NMD‚Äôs genetic causes‚Äîfailed to address other health issues arising as a result of this disorder, for patients exhibited heart and vascular issues at the time of diagnosis. As a result of this, young males with DMD and teenagers with BMD had yearly echocardiograms to detect premature cardiomyopathic signs.

Regular electrocardiograms were also prescribed for patients with MD and Emery-Dreifuss muscular dystrophy to screen for cardiac conduction disorders‚Äîabnormalities in the electrical system controlling the heart‚Äôs function and rhythm‚Äî that would make anti-arrhythmia drugs crucial. If Left Ventricular Ejection Fraction (LVEF) starts significantly decreasing in DMD patients, treatment beta-adrenoceptor blocker (e.g. bisoprolol) and an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors (e.g. perindopril) were prescribed immediately alongside occasional oral steroids; intake sometimes resulted in moderate hypertension (Strehle, 2009).

Those with DMD and SMA are prone to develop chest infections, which is due to their weak respiratory muscles and their reduced mobility and this was concluded in further paediatric myopathy and neuropathy management studies at the United Kingdom‚Äôs North Tyneside General Hospital. It was therefore recommended that they should have the pneumococcal and the seasonal influenza vaccines. Lower respiratory tract infections were treated aggressively with oral or intravenous antibiotics (Strehle, 2009).

At each clinic visit during the trial, patients' infected lung function was measured using an electronic spirometer with a printer that was connected to a dedicated app. The electronic spirometer was used to monitor pulmonary function, including forced vital capacity (FVC), forced expiratory volume in 1 second (FEV1), and peak expiratory flow (PEF). If symptoms of nocturnal hypoxia and hypercapnia were reported (e.g. headaches and tiredness in the morning), an overnight pulse oximetry study was arranged which allowed continuous oxygen saturation and provided heart rate recordings. This study‚Äôs objectives involved early recognition of oxygen desaturation‚Äîcrucial in preventing hypoxemia‚Äîand subjects the patient to respiratory distress (Strehle, 2009).

When a patient's coughing capacity, an indicator to the hypoxemia and hypercapnia, was significantly reduced, a mechanical insufflation-and-exsufflation device (CoughAssist¬Æ) was prescribed to remove secretions from the lungs. A steady decline in the Forced Vital Capacity (FVC) indicated the need for a home ventilation team referral and non-invasive positive pressure ventilation (NIPPV) via a nasal mask, a face mask, or a mouthpiece to prevent respiratory failure. A tracheostomy (surgical procedure that creates an opening in the neck into the trachea to facilitate breathing, often by inserting a tube) was rarely required (Strehle, 2009).

Like patients experiencing other chronic illnesses, children with NMDs should be regularly reviewed from an early age to increase life expectancy and improve quality of life. It is useful for physicians to take a structured approach when looking after these patients and monitor all affected organ systems. Ongoing research alongside clinical trials has demonstrated how newlyimproved drugs and care guidelines have improved many patients‚Äô lives. With such interventions, the healthcare community‚Äôs understanding of and the actions it takes to treat paediatric NMDs are bound to progress.

References

  1. Dowling, J. J., D Gonorazky, H., Cohn, R. D., & Campbell, C. (2018). Treating pediatric neuromuscular disorders: The future is now. American journal of medical genetics. Part A, 176(4), 804‚Äì841. https://doi.org/10.1002/ajmg.a.38418.
  2. Marchant, R. G., Bryen, S. J., Bahlo, M., Cairns, A., Chao, K. R., Corbett, A., Davis, M. R., Ganesh, V. S., Ghaoui, R., Jones, K. J., Kornberg, A. J., Lek, M., Liang, C., MacArthur, D. G., Oates, E. C., O'Donnell-Luria, A., O'Grady, G. L., Osei-Owusu, I. A., Rafehi, H., Reddel, S. W., ‚Ä¶ Cooper, S. T. (2024). Genome and RNA sequencing boost neuromuscular diagnoses to 62% from 34% with exome sequencing alone. Annals of clinical and translational neurology, 11(5), 1250‚Äì1266.
  3. Mendell, Jerry R., et al. "Single-dose gene-replacement therapy for spinal muscular atrophy." New England Journal of Medicine 377.18 (2017): 1713-1722.
  4. Strehle, Eugen-Matthias. "Long-term management of children with neuromuscular disorders." Jornal de pediatria 85 (2009): 379-384.

European Union Public Health Policy Papers

As part of ongoing collaborations with MediQuills and fellow biotech stakeholders, Revitalised Medicine and its founder have established partnerships between healthcare enthusiasts and organisations that communicate with the European Commission to advance new ideas within the healthcare, pharmaceutical, and biomedical research sectors.

These principles are key in driving some of the policy papers that have been published as part of this ongoing effort, and they are publicly available online through the Social Science Research Network.

Our Papers

Feedback on the EU‚Äôs Legislation on Medicines for Children and Rare Diseases

Enrique De La Cruz ¬∑ Sarah Khan ¬∑ Keshvee Sekhda ¬∑ Sydney Yerra ¬∑ Ridhi Gutta

MediQuills (United States) ¬∑ October 23, 2025

Executive Summary

Biotechnology for rare diseases and paediatric conditions has advanced substantially over the twenty-first century, particularly through recombinant technologies, biomarker integration, and mRNA-based platforms. Despite these scientific advances and nearly two decades of EU legislation intended to stimulate innovation, most paediatric rare diseases still lack authorised and effective treatments.

This paper examines the persistent translational gap between biotechnology innovation and pharmaceutical manufacturing, evaluates the historical performance of EU orphan and paediatric legislation, and proposes targeted reforms to strengthen regulatory flexibility, platform-based innovation, and long-term treatment accessibility.

Feedback on Blood, Tissues, and Cells for Medical Treatments ‚Äì Revised EU Rules (2022)

Sarah Khan ¬∑ Enrique De La Cruz ¬∑ Keshvee Sekhda ¬∑ Sydney Yerra ¬∑ Ridhi Gutta

MediQuills (United States) ¬∑ December 7, 2025

Executive Summary

Biotechnology for rare diseases and paediatric conditions has advanced substantially over the past two decades through recombinant technologies, biomarker-guided therapeutics, and nucleic-acid‚Äìbased platforms such as mRNA. Despite these advances, most rare and paediatric diseases still lack authorised treatments due to regulatory and translational bottlenecks.

This paper analyses the disconnect between biotechnology innovation and pharmaceutical manufacturing for specialised therapies and proposes targeted policy refinements to improve equitable access to therapies involving substances of human origin (SoHOs).

Through clear explanations, real-world examples, and uplifting stories, this book demystifies the work of oncologists‚Äîthe doctors who fight childhood cancer. Perfect for curious young minds, parents, and educators, The Power of Oncologists for Kids empowers children to see that medicine isn‚Äôt just about hospitals and treatments‚Äîit‚Äôs about resilience, kindness, and the power of never giving up.

Gastrointestinal Oncologies and Haematological Malignancies for Kids

Gastrointestinal Oncologies and Haematological Malignancies for Kids takes young readers on an eye-opening journey through the science of cancer‚Äîmade easy to understand, fascinating to explore, and full of hope.

From the stomach and intestines that help us digest food to the blood and bone marrow that keep us alive and energized, this book explains how certain cells can grow out of control and cause diseases known as cancers. Readers will learn what happens inside the body, how doctors detect and treat these illnesses, and how researchers are discovering new ways to help patients heal.

Written in a clear and compassionate way, this book helps kids understand some of the most complex topics in medicine‚Äîgastrointestinal cancers (like those in the stomach, liver, and pancreas) and blood cancers (like leukemia and lymphoma)‚Äîwhile celebrating the incredible progress being made in science and care.

How Does It Work: The Brain‚Äôs Brave Battle

How Does It Work: The Brain‚Äôs Brave Battle: Learning About Glioblastoma takes readers on an accessible and insightful journey into the biology, diagnosis, and treatment of glioblastoma, one of the most aggressive forms of brain cancer. The book breaks down complex medical science into clear explanations while weaving in real-life stories of patients, families, and medical professionals facing this disease.

Readers gain a deeper understanding of how glioblastoma develops, how doctors approach treatment, and the challenges and hope associated with current and emerging therapies. Combining education with empathy, this book empowers readers with knowledge and inspires appreciation for the courage and resilience of those affected.

Lungs Under Cancerous Attack for Kids

Lungs Under Cancerous Attack for Kids dives deep into the amazing world of our lungs‚Äîthe organs that help us breathe every second of every day‚Äîand what happens when dangerous cancer cells try to take over. With easy-to-understand explanations and vivid illustrations, this book helps kids discover how healthy lungs work, why cancer sometimes starts, and how scientists and doctors fight back using powerful treatments like chemotherapy, radiation, and immunotherapy.

Readers will explore how tiny cells can turn harmful, how the body‚Äôs defense system responds, and how research is giving patients more hope than ever before.

Perfect for curious kids who love science, medicine, or helping others, Lungs Under Cancerous Attack for Kids makes complex medical ideas simple, engaging, and empowering‚Äîshowing that even in the toughest battles, knowledge, care, and innovation can save lives.
